column14: First of all I rarely leave reviews but I will for these because I love these boots! They are made of soft and luxurious leather. column14: These are simple to install (2 seconds) and they really help with biking.  When going on longer trails from sunlight to shade, these really brighten the shade while taking edge off glare.  Also feels really comfortable for the eyes in slightly cloudy to rainy conditions.  I like them while driving a car too. Only time I need something darker is when it is really bright and no shade in sight (like mid day, full sun).  I clipped these on my prescription plastic glasses that also have darkening capability and are small sized enough to prevent fogging up.  My glasses are never quite dark enough.  This yellow clip on keeps my regular glasses more light grey, rather than darkening completely, which is actually great in most conditions.  When I go into the shade normally, my regular glasses stay dark for awhile, whereas with these clip ons I don't feel like I'm going into a tunnel.  I like that I can flip the shades up briefly to get more light.  Best of both worlds.  I also bought a different brand darker pair of flip shades which I like too, but finding I am using the yellow ones more.  Also like that they are inexpensive, so if they get lost, broken or stolen I don't feel too much of a loss.  I'll just get another one!

column6: Women's Polarized Sunglasses High Quality Driving Sun Glasses Female Fashion Elegant Sunglasses
column14: I do not usually buy sunglasses online because I like to see how I look with them on. I took a chance and I chose a pair that have a similar cut to sunglasses I use almost every day.  These glasses are very nice to look through.  The view is quite clear.  They are definitely polarized.  The amount of tint is just right, i.e., dark enough to wear in the sun but not too dark to wear in a building.  They are lightweight and comfortable.  I like the skinny ear pieces because I like to have all the peripheral vision I can get, and some of the wider ear pieces block my vision.  These glasses are very nice for the money.  I think they are perfect for my vacation.  I have had these new glasses for a couple of weeks at the time of this writing.

column6: New Balance Men's MW759 Country Walking Shoe
column14: The purpose of buying a EEEE width shoe is to accommodate a WIDE foot, which is usually widest at the forward part of the foot.  The toe box on these shoes is entirely too narrow to fit comfortably on a EEEE width foot and the arch support is poor. I have worn them, so I guess that I'm stuck with them, but I wouldn't buy them again. I have removed the inner soles and replaced them with orthotics that provide much better arch support, but that doesn't compensate for the uncomfortably narrow toe box. I've always liked New Balance shoes, but they need to go back to the 966 style toe box on their wide shoes.

column14:
I recently moved to an area with grocery stores within walking distance, and it felt wasteful to go for a few items and have to take a plastic, or paper bag. I would also feel concerned about the strength of the bags when buying a 6 pack of beer, so I searched on The Sweet Home, and this bag was one that was recommended. I went ahead and bought it, and when it arrived I was happy that the color of the bag was as it appeared on my screen, and the bag was bigger than I imagined it would be.

I've had many trips to the grocery store within walking distance, and a few to Aldi as well, and every time I use this bag it's such a pleasure. It seriously holds so much stuff and the material is very high quality, I don't worry that any boxes or plastic containers will puncture/tear/rip the bag, however it's not so bulky that I can't sloppily fold it and put it in it's little pouch without struggling to make it fit. The straps are also thick, so if you put it over your shoulder, they don't painfully dig into your arm when the bag is as full as it can get.

column6: KEEN Men's Newport H2 Sandal
column13: Almost perfect -- but still very happy with the Shoe
column14:
I purchased theses a few months ago so have been wearing them a lot..... I've had a pair of Keen H2 Sandals for 6-7 years and love them. They finally gave up the ghost and so I needed a new pair. My old sandals were a size 9.5 so i decided to order a 9.5 again. WRONG, these were to small and had to exchange them for a size 10. These fit almost perfectly. they still felt a bit snug in the width and the length was about right but my 9.5s still seemed a bit longer. However, the more I wear them the more cofortable they become in the width and length so I'm guessing they are stretching out that little bit.

For those wanting these sandals for boating, I sail a lot and race. I wear my sandals for cruising, they work great since your toes are protected and provide enough grip for what I need when cruising. As for racing I where regular sailing shoes that are made to grip. If I was only in hte cockpit then I might wear my sandals but I tend to wear my racing shoes.

Heat build up -- If I walk around on warm pavement my feet do tend to get hot in these sandals. This happened with my old sandal and is the reason I gave them 4 stars. That said, they don't get hot enough where they are uncomfortable but they will get a little warm. THis is one thing that I did not expect.

Overall these are great shoes and the only sandal I own. They are comfortable (even if a little warm) but they meet all my needs.

column6: Harley-Davidson Men's Badlands Motorcycle Boot
column13: 2nd pair of Harley boots I've owned . . .1st pair lasted for years which makes them worth the price!!!
column14:
I specifically went looking for Harley boots last year (2014 -- yes I'm a little late on my review), because my 1st pair were comfy and lasted me for so many years. My only complaint is your feet can get extremely cold if you don't wear the appropriate socks. I live in MA and we had a brutal winter last year between the cold and the snow, but as long as I had nice thick socks on my feet stayed warm and dry. I recommend these boots to anyone looking to make an investment because you won't be needing another pair as long as you use leather protector / waterproofing spray and only wear them in the winter for the same purpose as myself. If you live somewhere like MA that is . . . as far as wearing them all year long I would guess they stay in great shape for a few years too.

These particular boots zip on the side making it easy putting them on and taking them off which is why I tried this style versus the same I had as before + they're a bit taller. I hope this helps someone making a decision . . . Harley Davidson makes quality products!!!

column6: ECCO Men's Yura GTX Fashion Sneaker
column13: Great Shoe and I have Foot Problems.
column14:
I have chronic plantar fasciitis. For years. The best I have managed is to get it so I am not always in bad pain (tried it all, custom insoles, braces, steroid shots, PT, etc.) . Walking in the wrong shoes is just about the worst thing I can do to aggravate things. I knew I was spending two months overseas and that I would be walking a lot. For an extremely shallow reason (I saw some dude wearing ECO golf shoes on the street), I decided to buy these. At $160, I thought I was a fool, but I did it anyway.

Well, I have been wearing these things all day for three months now. I walked 5-10 miles a day in 95F weather. Streets, hiking, everything. I won't claim that they cured my foot problem, but they did not make it worse. In fact, I felt less foot fatigue after the long periods of time on my feet. They have great traction, are study and free of defects aside from some staining. The manufacturing quality is impressive. Looking at the tread and outsides, and the insoles all seem like new (again, aside from some stains).

I had never even heard of ECOs before buying these. I lucked out.

column13: Fit true to size and seem nice and warm!
column14:
I wear a women's size 8. In most sheepskin/ shearling shoes and slippers, I buy a 7 because they stretch. So, I bought these in a 7 and they were just too tight. There seemed to be no give in them.

I sent them back to Amazon and am awaiting my size 8s. I am assuming they should fit perfectly.

Quality seemed good. The bottom can completely come out, which means you can buy Ugg inserts and put them in and you have new slippers! (My other sheepskin ones (Bearpaw Loki 2) didn't have removable inserts and I wore them until the shearling was gone. I looked at the Ugg ones and would have bought those, but the bottom insoles didn't come out of those either.

Only thing I didn't like was that I paid, $53 for the lime green size 7s. 2 days later, I had to pay $69 for any of the size 8s. I wish Amazon would let you exchange items and get the same price.

I took 1 star off, just because I do not know the longevity of the slippers yet. I will update after a few months to let you know!

These boots are by far the best,  most comfortable, durable and  economically priced boots I have ever worn.  This will be my 4th purchase of these boots... column6: Filson Highlander Boot - Men's Size 10.5
column14: In my opinion, these are probably Filson's best boots. Filson uses an "old fashion" type of insulation of wool and leather. That is, wool is "sandwiched" between the outside leather and an inner leather lining. The outside leather is thick but very supple and the leather lining provides significant comfort. Contrary to my review of the waterproof uplander boot which I found to be extremely narrow in width, the highlanders fit as expected. I normally wear a size 10 M in an unlined boot and a 10.5 M in a lined boot such as the highlanders and the 10.5 fit perfectly. I think the leather lining will prove to provide comfort not only for a couple of hours but for an entire day. As with all of Filson products, the highlander is expensive but is worth every penny.

column6: LifeStride Women's Yolder Gladiator Sandal
column14: Very nice shoes. I love, love, love gladiator shoes in pewter, and these fit the bill! It's true that they're a little longer than normal when I'm sitting, but when I stand up, my foot expands (I have a high arch, though, and a shoe saleswoman pointed out to me once that hight arches DO expand a lot in length when standing) to fill that empty space. I have had strangers compliment me on my cute shoes, and ask what brand they are. They aren't 100% comfortable (let's say, they're 90% comfortable), but I have not developed any blisters wearing them in the past few months I've been wearing them, so, as far as I'm concerned, they're pretty good, and will probably become even more comfortable over time. Two things that are essential when I'm trying on sandals (or shoes in general), are comfort, cushion, and traction on the bottom, as, I don't know about you, but I HATE slip-sliding around due to slick shoe bottoms. In these sandals, both the cushion and the traction are good!

column6: Bloch Dance Dansoft Ballet Slipper (Toddler/Little Kid)
column13: Amazing quality at a great price!  Fits my daughter perfect!
column14:
I am very impressed with the Bloch Dance Dansoft Ballet Slipper! I can tell it is fabricated with excellent quality. Most importantly, my daughter loves them! I was a little worried about ordering ballet shoes online, but after reading the reviews I was comfortable with what size I should order my daughter. She is only 3 and wears a size 9 in shoes. When we tried on the ballet slippers at Payless I had her in a 10 and it was too wide (plus the quality was not very good). After reading the reviews I ordered a half size bigger, so I got her a 9.5 M (what I received was a 9.5 D, the reviews have very helpful hints for what size to order). When I took the ballet slippers out I was worried they weren't going to fit her. They looked small, but they actually fit perfect with a little bit of room in the toes! I am so glad I ordered a half size bigger instead of a full size! The ties on the front can be pulled to make sure the slipper fits her foot perfect. She didn't want to take her shoes off she was so excited! So, I was able to get a better quality ballet slipper for a lower cost than Payless! Overall, I would highly recommend these ballet slippers!!!!

Pictured below: I hadn't tightened the strings of the bow yet, my daughter was too excited to have them on!

column6: Coleman Women's CC1 6024 Polarized Sunglasses Audrey Hepburn Style
column13: Extremely pleased with my new pair of polarized sunglasses!
column14:
I have been looking for a new pair of polarized sunglasses for the longest time. I am glad to have come across Coleman's Polarized sunglasses which feature an oversized frame with beautiful accents. It fits perfectly on my face (I am square faced), stylish, frames are lightweight, durable and since I like wearing it on top of my head at times, I am glad that it won't stretch out if done that way. The lenses are polarized to eliminate glare and block 100%UV (ABC).

It came with a black drawstring bag to protect it while it's inside your purse. One thing missing is the microfiber cloth for cleaning, but I have lots of that at home so it's perfectly fine. I have sensitivity to light (major migraine trigger) and this is the perfect sunglasses for me! I am extremely pleased with this purchase! If you're out and about, I highly recommend you get one for yourself!

I received this product at a discount in exchange for my honest and unbiased review.

column6: Ariat Women's Round Up Square Toe Western Cowboy Boot
column14:
Before purchasing these, I read reviews about size and fit on other styles. I've been wearing boots since I could walk, and some brands fit larger or smaller than others. I just want to say to everyone to ignore all the comments and reviews from city dwellers who seem to give a bad review on a boot because they don't know how it's supposed to look and feel. Under no circumstances is a boot supposed to feel comfortable. I'm originally from the mid west so I know. Boots are for work, not city girl fashion, but if you must wear it, keep in mind that it is a feeling one must get used to.
I love the Ariat brand and they do run a little big. You also must keep in mind the style of toe you order. The more pointed the toe, the bigger you might want to get for some wiggle room on the toes. I've only worn this pair a few days and yes they are tight slipping on, but once on there is plenty of room. I wear a size 6 women's, and I ordered a 5.5. There is still a little room but anything smaller would miss my arch. They rub against the top of my foot, but they're made so they don't fall off when riding. They will loosen up as you wear them. Not wearing to the club, I mean walking in them around a rough yard, thats when you'll feel the break in. Wear them as much as you can to break them in. This style seems to be so that jeans can be tucked in to them, that's why there is a wider calf. If you want that city girl look where they hug your calves while wearing shorts or dresses, try getting a child size and that should do the trick. These also look good with jeans pulled over. The design matches with nearly everything, and I got lots of compliments on them.

column6: Merrell Men's Phoenix Ventilator Hiking Shoe
column14:
This is a great pair of shoes, depending on what you're going to use them for. I had originally bought them as a "do it all" summer shoe. I wanted something that was comfortable to wear all day and walk in for extended periods, but that also looked good enough to wear with shorts and a nice shirt for a casual night out (something a notch up from standard tennis shoes, with my thought being that something tan/neutral in color would do the job). They do great for the former, not so much for the latter.

First, the good:
- Fit me true-to-size
- Very durable, good quality
- Comfortable to wear for extended periods
- Tread not overly-aggressive (as compared to other Merrell hiking shoes
- Looks fine with jeans or other casual long pants

Where it missed for me:
- Quite a "clunky" shoe, befitting some time out on the trail or other "outdoorsy" activity, but would perhaps look a little goofy/clunky/heavy duty for use at the pool, or if trying to dress "dress casual" with shorts and a nice shirt for a night out.

And believe me, I am anything but "Mr. Fashion", and most of us are pretty laid back and casual here in Texas as far as dress goes. But it just wasn't the shoe I was looking for for this purpose.

They are actually the shoes I use to mow the yard in now, and they are perfect for this. I would also not hesitate to use them for a light hike (though I have some other hiking shoes I'd likely use instead) or simply for wearing with jeans or other casual long pants around town. They are comfortable. Just look a little goofy with nice shorts/shirt for going out to dinner or whatever.

column6: Bostonian Men's Calhoun Limit Oxford
column13: Great value dress shoe at this price point (around $100)
column14:
Great value dress shoe at this price point (around $100).
This shoe style (Bostonian Calhoun Limit) and Bostonian Akron can be found most places for around $100, and I continue to keep this Bostonian line as part of my wardrobe due to their durability.
This is a classic Cap-Toe Oxford that can be worn with jeans, khakis, slacks or suits.
(The dark Burgundy color goes with Anything you might wear)
In my experience, I expect about a full year of daily office use (5 days a week) before the bottom (typically in the heel) shows wear.
I have never worn though the soles of this Bostonian shoe in under a year (but I have worn out soles in 3 other comparable brands in under a year)
Sizing accuracy: I wear a size 11 and this Calhoun allows slightly more room than an average 11, which works out great for me. Very comfortable.
Amazon has the best prices for these by a long shot (better than Clark's, DSW, Zappos,& the Bostonian outlet [2nd best price])

column14: Wow, these ankle boots (Sketchers) fit fantastic. First of all the shipping was faster than expected. Next, the quality of this item is superb. As soon as I put them on I could feel the comfort and as usual with all the Sketchers I have bought there is no breakin period needed.  I liked this item so much that I ordered a second pair so I could switch between the two. I also immediately prepped them with mink oil (as I do with all my boots/shoes I get). Putting on regular shoe wax would eventually darken the stitch seams (which I absolutely love) so hence only using mink oil (and saddlesoap prior to future mink oil if my boots get too dirty). column6: Five Ten Men's Canyoneer 3 Water Shoe
column13: Mesh panels and loose ankles let in a lot of debris
column14: Been using these for caving for over a month now.  They've seen everything from dry vertical caves to chest high stream caves to expansive mudflats.  They've held up, but I can see some areas that might start to give out.. the mesh panels aren't the best material for caving, and the laces are not durable at all, but the Stealth rubber soles and rand seem durable and really helps with technical climbs.  My only real complaint so far is that they are not snug around the ankles, and a LOT of debris gets in.  I wouldn't use these at all for very sandy places.  Unfortunately, that and mud are where the Canyoneer 3's soles really shine with their sticky and deep lugs compared to the Adidas Hydros.  The Hydros on the other hand, which are getting extremely hard to find, keep debris out with the integrated ankle strap and no mesh panels.  Also, the Canyoneers seemed true to size at size 10 (maybe a little wide, which is good for me), while the Hydros were a half to full size bigger than the Canyoneers in a 10.  Overall, I like both shoes and use the Canyoneers for 'dry mud' and technical caves with little water and the Hydros for anywhere that has a lot of water, sand, and/or loose debris.  I think the Adidas are a bit more of an all-around shoe.

column14:
Shipping:
They do not ship to APO, at least they didnt to me. Odd because Mostly military buy this boot. I had to ship to my house back in the states and have my parents fwd them. took about 2 days to get to my house in the states and about 4 days to get to me here in Germany

Product:
So i mean.. they are boots. Belleville makes good products, i always buy from them! however.. for some reason they sent me the wrong color boots. I ordered Coyote brown, they sent me Desert Tan. (still in regulation so its really just an annoyance.)

The fit:
as expected, my last pair was a 10W and they were a bit too wide. These are also a bit too wide, but i thought the 9.5 would make up for it. Still a good fit, not perfect.. maybe a 10R would do better. (i typically wear 9.5-10w in most shoes/boots)

My advice:
Ensure youre willing to get the wrong color boot. Or the wrong kind. Or you are willing to send it back if they do send you the wrong ones.

one star, because well... I didn't get the product i bought. I got something completely different.

column14: I have wide flat feet. I am a perfect 9.5 EEE, not 9.5W, or 9.5 EW or 9.5 XW. column6: Lacoste Women's Showcourt RQT Fashion Sneaker
column14:
Take note of the word "fashion" in this sneaker's description: it is not a flexible, lightweight shoe suitable for sports or fitness. Instead, this is a minimal-design shoe that looks great with a casual summertime outfit when you're basically just hanging around or walking around.

On a cruise, at the beach, visiting your pals at their lake house, watching a ballgame---these clean white sneakers are comfortable, yet still look polished enough to stop off at a restaurant or bar without looking like a slob who just came from the gym. Pair with a Polo shirt and seersucker skirt or Bermuda shorts: casual but classy.

The leather is firm, not thin, so these keep their shape instead of stretching out into a sloppy mess. Easy to keep clean as well. These are heavier than many athletic shoes, true; they last a lot longer (and still look new) with proper care. Well worth the investment to have one pair of sneakers in the closet for certain summer occasions.

column6: Teva Men's Toachi 2 Sandal
column14: I bought these sandals specifically for hiking in the backcountry of the Colorado Rockies. For a number of years I was using the Teva Obern sandal which was a great sandal for all types of terrain, talus, scree, boulders, tundra and trails. So when Teva stopped making the Obern I had to find a new sandal, bummer. It was between the Toachi 2 and the Terra FI 4, I ended up choosing the Toachi for two reasons, the water draining feature which is really awesome since I have to forge through creeks and lakes often when off trail and the plastic clip which is great for everyday use. When I got this sandal out in the backcountry I found out this sandal is totally designed for boat use. It has absolutely no use in the backcountry since there is very little tread and the foot bed is very flimsy. I've taken this sandal out in the backcountry four times on 10-15 mile hikes often with no trail and every time I have taken a fall because of the sandals and I almost never fall. The last fall I took I did some damage to my toes and I will be out for recovery for at least six weeks before I can aggressively start hiking again. For everyday use this sandal is very comfortable but that's not what I need. I found a pair of Obern's on Ebay but they are a half size to big so if they do not work I'll give the FI 4 a try and see how they compare to the Obern which was a bomb proof sandal.

column6: Calvin Klein Reversible N/S Novelty Tote Bag
column14: Not too sure yet.  It just arrived in UPS and I immediately turned it inside out because I wanted the white for summer.  Unfortunately this is not truly reversible in the strictest sense of the word.  You see there is the little zip pouch on a leash that clips to the inside of the bag?  All the hooks for clipping it are mounted on the white side of the bag.  Yes, I could clip it to the handle clasps, but then I have these random D-rings sticking out on the white side.  Also, the handles are only black, which is going to look silly with the white side out.  I'd expected the handles to be white on one side and black on the other.  Lastly, there is a 'Made in China' tag sewn down so that when the white side is out, this tag sticks out.  I could cut it off, and if I keep this bag, I will, but am not sure yet.  Initially I was hesitant to pay this price for PVC when there are many other reversible totes that are a lot cheaper, but this one looks dressier overall and that was nice.  Except that with the white side out, the tag, black straps, and D-rings for the inner pouch make it look cheap.  Edited a couple hours later:  those d-rings are for the crossbody strap, and since I have an ivory crossbody strap around here somewhere, I may yet keep this...depends if I can accustom myself to the black short straps.  Note that I had to go to Macy's website to look at pictures and figure this out!

column6: Thin OPTICS Stick Anywhere, Go Everywhere Reading Glasses plus Universal Pod Case
column13: Lenses scratched up with light use, but still great glasses.
column14:
I had been seriously shopping for a pair of folding glasses for some time to toss in my pocket to use at restaurants and the like. When I saw a news segment about these glasses I immediately came on to Amazon and, Lo!, there they were. Mostly, I think these things are great. I bought the "universal case" and simply carry it in my pocket for the times when I'm without my reading glasses (restaurants, in a meeting, on a plane, etc.). I've never gotten the impression they are to be considered replacements for ones regular reading glasses and they're not. With that said, they sit comfortably and firmly on my nose and I never feel like they are going to slip off and, at the same time, they are light enough to be comfortable to wear for longer periods if need be.

With that said, my one complaint about them, and this is why I only rated them 3 stars, is that the lenses have scratched quite noticeably. I've been using these glasses for about a month now and most of that time they are in the case in my pocket and, still, they are pretty scratched up. I'm not sure if there is some lint/dirt from my pocket making its way into the case and causing the scratching or what the issue is. When I read the product description, I read "shatter-proof lenses" as "scratch resistant" as well - apparently that isn't the case. As another reviewer mentioned, maybe lining the case with felt or some other material would mitigate the issue.

Overall, I would, and still do, recommend these glasses to people, but now caveat my recommendation with the warning about scratching. If they get a handle on the scratched lens issue, this would be a 5 star review, no questions asked.

column6: Mizuno Women's Wave Inspire 11 Running Shoe
column13: I am very disappointed by this purchase
column14: I am very disappointed by this purchase.  I recently bought this pair of shoes at a local running store (like within the past 3 months) and thought that I would buy another pair since I liked them so much.  I opted to buy them on Amazon because I have Prime and there is a 10% discount.  I was a bit nervious about this, because who buys a pair of shoes without trying them on, right?  But I figured if I already had a pair, wouldn't they just fit exactly like my current pair? Wrong. First, I received the package on a rainy day, and it was left outside on my porch until I came home from work.  This isn't normally a problem, but it was packaged in a plastic shipping bag, with the Mizuno shoes in a cardboard shoe box inside.  When I opened the package, the cardboard box was mushy, and soaked.  The plastic packaging was not sufficient for rainy weather.  Luckily the shoes were not terribly soaked or too wet. I've worn the shoes exactly three times for at least 2 mile walks on my treadmill (to break them in). Second, I can't believe that these are the same pair of Mizuno shoes.  They feel NOTHING like the other comfy, cushiony pair that I already had.  Again, these are the exact same style (albeit a different color), so I can't figure out why they are hard, rigid, offer little arch support, and feel like there is absolutely no cushioning.  I find it hard to believe that I haven't broken them in enough, because the other pair of shoes I bought in-store felt perfect the moment I tried them on.  Needless to say, I will be returning these shoes to Amazon. From this process I learned a valuable lesson: just pay the extra money to get the shoes at my local running store. It's not worth the time and hassle I've invested in this.

column6: CLIMB X Rockmaster Climbing Shoe with FREE Climbing DVD ($30 Value)
column13: They're cheap in both price and quality.
column14:
Update: these went from a 4 star to a 1. Why? Because they broke down fast. Honestly - I absolutely loved these shoes the first few weeks. They fit great, performed well, etc. (see original review below). 5 weeks in, however, they had developed a hole on the upper, by one of the laces. I found that peculiar, because I hadn't been particularly aggressive with them. I contacted Climb X customer service to see if they'd warranty the shoe. They replied that they don't do that because people have "different climbing styles". I'm sorry - but if these piece of crap shoes can't withstand 5 weeks of moderate indoor climbing, they're worthless. I get that it's a cheap intro level shoe, and I'm not expecting pro quality - but at least moderate durability. They're garbage. Spend a few extra bucks on some La Sportivas or Scarpas.

Original review:
--
I've worn these shoes for 15 straight days of indoor bouldering now, each session ~2 hours in length, and I'm VERY pleased with them. The price was of course great, but what I didn't expect was the quality. They fit great - I'm normally a size 10.5 and I was advised to size down for climbing shoes, but I tried them on in person, and the 10.5 fit me well. My toes curl in slightly, and they're just breaking in now and seem to fit perfectly.

I like the ridged heel, and personally, I like the toe on these, though I think they're not for everyone. Some folks like a pointier toe, but I prefer mine just a bit squared. I'm an intermediate climber and I think these will last me a while. The hemp footbed is one of my favorite features because it has so far withstood my stinky feet and doesn't seem to retain any odors.

column6: FitFlop Women's Goodstock Dress Sandal
column14: I like these sandals, but they are not 100% perfect.  First the pros: The insole is more cushy (slightly spongy) than all my previous FifFlop sandals.  Nice! I ordered the dark olive.  It is a slightly brushed/nubuck leather that goes with many colors: most shades of brown plus black, gray and some shades of green etc. The straps allow for some adjustability. They can be worn with all length of pants:  long, medium and short to r-e-a-l-ly short!  Skirts too. They were comfortable right out of the box, and I can wear them happily all day....even when my feet quickly turn from normal to disgustingly puffy!! The arch support is a pretty good one. This is a style that just might appeal to young as well as the mature ladies.  Now the cons: They run looong!  I have learned from experience that this brand usually runs big, and I do allow for that when making a purchase.  I have learned to buy a size smaller than my normal size when purchasing FitFlops.  I ordered my usual size 7 (38) which is the size of  ALL  of my  FitFlops, and that is quite a few.  This pair; however, allows for a good 1/2-3/4 inch of sole beyond my toes.  Yes, I probably should have exchanged them, but the size is just o.k......not perfect.  This sandal runs LARGE.....at least for me.  As mentioned in the pros:  The straps allow for some adjustability; however, there will be some velcro showing if you have to loosen the straps more than a smidge.  Since the velcro is the same color as the shoe that does not spoil the appearance of the shoe very much. The straps may stick out if you have to tighten them more than a smidge to get a desirable fit. These sandals, in fact this brand, will probably not be suitable for a narrow foot.  They also run a bit wider than lots of other brands.  I do recommend these sandals, but keep in mind they may be a bit long....and maybe a smidge wide for some feet.

column6: Saucony Men's Cohesion 8 Running Shoe
column14: Over the past 30 years, Ive trjed practically every brand of athletic shoe on the market.  I keep on returning to Saucony, for their fit, comfort, and durability.  The Cohesion model also has the wonderful advantage of reasonable cost.  I really wear my sneakers, some every day, some days all day, for street walking, tromping around in moderate woods, doing yard work, etc.  Sauconys handle everything and stay comfortable.  My one gripe, and it's not a major one, is that over the past five years or so, the tongue in every pair of Sauconys I've had has had a tendency to move, leaving a gap between the rest of the shoe and the tongue.  Not sure what causes this, but it's more of an aesthetic than a wearability issue.

column14:
I got these insoles as a treatment for a case of plantar faciitis. However, I now wish I had purchased the version which provides more support. Without a doubt, these insoles are good but I think more arch support would have been more therapeutic in the treatment of my malady. As you might expect, using these will may require that you remove the "OEM" insole from you shoe. If you don't do this, then the fit of your shoe may be a bit tight on the top and this will require a loosening of the laces.

As mentioned, these insoles are comfortable and I can walk all day. I just wish they were a quicker remedy for my plantar faciitis.

column6: Altra Men's Instinct Everyday Fashion Sneaker
column14: The front part is nice and wide like all Altra shoes but the back needs some work. The area around the heel is cushier on the outside than it is on the inside and it doesn't hold the back of your foot very well. The top edge behind the Achilles is a little too pointy and can dig into your leg after a while, but adding an aftermarket stick on pad to the wall there helped fix a lot of these issues. The laces could also use another set of holes further back to help hold the shoe more securely. Aside from the heel area these shoes are solid and quite comfy for long periods of time and it's the only way I can sneak barefoot shoes into work meetings or places with a dress code.

column13: 1st review... More as soon as the smell goes away
column14:
***UPDATE*** Now 5‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê
Lol it took 9months+ but the smell is completely gone! NOW I get to enjoy using this awesome huge purse‚úî
I've had this purse for 4days...Overall it's great! Exactly as described. I got the Tan color,it's gorgeous. Very good quality workmanship. Love the "antiquing" of the hardware and zippers. All zippers move very smoothly. As others have said, the front outside pocket will hold a pen or two. I think it's mainly decorative. The back outside pocket is good sized. The handles are very sturdy, I personally love the rolled handles as I think it looks & feels better in hand than flat would. The attachable strap is very long and we'll made also. Inside there's 2 side pockets for a cell (I've got a Samsung Galaxy S5 & it fits completely) and either a small wallet or keys, so they don't fall into the abyss of this huge purse, they're both trimmed with a leather-like darker brown band on top. There's also a large inside zippered pocket. The lining inside seems very strong overall The top zipper is great because I just don't trust magnetic snaps... Now on to the smell ~ oh my goodness it's horrible. I opened a pkg of snuggle dryer sheets and used the entire 30 sheets to try and lesson the ucky nasty kinda fishy odor. Just stuck them into every opening and everyplace inside. I throughly sprayed fabreeze on the outside also. I'm hoping that this will resolve it to the point that I don't gag when I'm holding it. I really love this purse! And sincerely can't wait to actually use it. Just need to get the smell gone. Then it'll be a 5+ ‚òÜ review.

column6: Khombu Women's Mallory Boot
column13: Beauty, Comfortable And Quality Workmanship Make These A Winner!
column14:
These boots are so much better than I could have ever anticipated. I do wish they were a bit higher but these days I really don't think you can find a functional quality winter boot that comes to the knee like when I was a kid.

The boots come about 1/2 way up my calf and they are wide enough at the top so that I can tuck in my jeans without problem. They are extremely comfortable and run just a bit big. I wear a 10 and they have enough room that I can wear my wool hunting socks in them without being too tight. The zipper part is my favorite I think. I have been wearing Bear Paw boots for the last six years and though they are nice and warm they would hurt my feet and legs because of no arch support. These do have support. They are very well made and should last me at least six more years thus for the $48 and change I paid for them, they won't owe me a dime. The brown color is nice and dark more like a dark chestnut.

If you are looking for a pair of boots and have wide feet or wide calves give these a try. They are stylish, comfortable, well made and just plain worth it. I'm more than happy with my choice and I'm picky!

column13: Eell made shoes but sizing is inconsistent
column14:
Well made and handsome shoes but sizing is inconsistent with other timberland ...

As it turns out (to my surprise) I own quite a few Timberland shoes and their sizing is all over the place so I can't quite comment whether the sizing is correct... I normally wear 43 - most of my shoes are in that size; Timberland shoes are the exception. I have Wodehouse Chukkas in 9D (the label on the shoe says it's size 43), and I can wear them with a thick wooly sock without feeling too constricted. My boat shoes are 9.5W (the label also says it's size 43) - feel great naked and with a thin sock. These I got in 9W (yes, it's size 43, according to the label) based on other reviewers' recommendations to size down and they are way too tight for my wide feet even without a sock.

column6: ASICS Women's GEL-Contend 2 Running Shoe
column13: This is a neutral shoe but it has great support and fits my wide feet quite well
column14: I am a female runner (Jeff's wife) with a size 10 foot and I always wear 11 in Asics. I've been wearing this brand for 7 years straight and can tell you for sure that fit and quality does NOT correlate with price! This is why I always buy my Asics on Amazon and if I'm not familiar with a particular model, I look it up on the Asics website to see what kind of shoe it is. This is a neutral shoe but it has great support and fits my wide feet quite well. Perhaps if you have a smaller foot, the shoe is built more narrow, but in an 11 it is plenty wide. If for some reason it doesn't have enough cushion for you, you can get gel heel cups which are a MIRACLE for those of us who tend toward plantar fasciitis (I use Spenco brand, also from Amazon). But this is a supportive, lightweight shoe and I recommend it. There truly is NO NEED to spend 100 bucks on running shoes! It isn't the most beautiful running shoe out there, but who cares! :)

column14: Not a bad pair of cheaper sunglasses at all. Both its lenses are equally dark and have the same polarization effect. At first I thought I was being lied to that the frames were metal when they sounded like plastic when tapped and scratched with your fingernail, but they are definitely aluminum as I can't even bend the ear piece and they feel solid when you fold them. They feel comfortable when I wear them and I can even adjust the nose pads by bending them carefully since they are also metal. Some reviewers say that these glasses stick out away from their faces too much, but for me they don't at all since my eye sockets are a little deeper to where the top of the frame just barely touches my lower forehead. The sides of the lenses don't block the sun 100% if the bothers you, but they are more than adequate for me. I like the little screwdriver it comes with. It has 2 ends, one being a straight end and the other being a phillips end. Both sides have caps that you screw on and even a have tiny rubber o-rings. Overall very good to me.

column6: Baggallini Horizon Crossbody
column14: This handbag is very attractive. Construction is excellent. The seams are even, the stitching well done and the hardware is polished but sturdy. I was a little worried at not being able to touch the fabric. No problem. It not only has good weight, it has a slightly polished sheen to it. I expect it will stand up to years of use. Now to the inside. The design is well thought and just as well constructed. The outer compartments, two on front and one in back, zip easily and have good room for cell phone, ipod, digital camera in front and mini ipad or kindle in back. Inside there are 5 credit card pockets on the right with a flat deep pocket behind them, a cell phone size pocket on the left, AND and an inner zipped pocket nearly the size of the whole purse. Also, there is an attached key fob and an attached coin purse. I purchased the aquamarine color and the inside fabric is silk-like and light yellow. The strap as it arrived is perfect length for over the shoulder. It is easy to make it longer for cross body use. March 28,2016  Update: Still loving this Bag and just bought another in a different color. Took it on a trip and am still amazed that not only can I get in everything, I can find it!

column13: but there is nothing wrong with it - it's a great bag. It gets 4 because
column14:
I'm giving this bag 4 stars, but there is nothing wrong with it - it's a great bag. It gets 4 because, though I wanted a medium size bag, it's just a little smaller than I thought. I have the SakRoots XL wallet, and it fits fine in the bag but there's not much room for anything else. Also, the cell phone slit on the outside back fits a smart phone, but not one with any kind of a protective case - I have an otterbox on a Galaxy 5S and it won't fit in the slot, so I have to put it inside the bag. And one last thing is that the pockets on the inside are very shallow - they don't go all the way down to the bottom of the bag, so pens or sunglasses won't go in the pockets.
I love the color, the style, and the drop on the handle is perfect - which is really hard to find - it's just not quite big enough for me.

column6: Ecco Footwear Womens Chase II Lace Shoe
column14:
Why would you spend $120 on a pair of very ordinary looking sneakers? If your answer was 'comfort,' then keep on looking.

I know everybody's feet are different, and this shoe has a lot of great reviews- that's why I bought a pair. But I thought it would be fair to the prospective buyer to counterbalance all the other reviews by adding my experience, which has been terrible. I had read several reviews about no break-in period, and one that said something about throwing them in a suitcase for a trip, and then walking all around in them. That last bit in particular got my attention. My dog had eaten my two very comfortable pairs of sneakers (my fault, I should not have left them out). I had put off replacing them for a month or two, but then I needed to take a trip.

When I got these, I found they were kinda cute-ugly, perfectly fine for ordinary activities. I walked around the house a little, and didn't find any major issues. They have a hard rubber bottom, nothing special. You can't tell from looking at them, but there is a little bit of heel, maybe between 1/4 and 1/2 an inch. You can feel it when you're standing in them. The leather is nice. Wasn't really sure why they cost more than my running sneakers, but they were fine. I also haven't had issues with shoes in years, so I wasn't particularly worried about it. (Again, that is why I am willing to spend more money on shoes; comfort is fairly important to me.)

BIG mistake. I got blisters and blisters. Right at the back of the heel. To the right of that. To the left of that. Above that. Holy cow. Talk about hobbling around. AND these shoes make my feet fall asleep while I am wearing them. Strange, I know. I tried pulling out the insole and using a pair of my beloved Superfeet (special insoles), but the shoe was too shallow for this to work well. So now these shoes are relegated to short trips to the supermarket. And even so, I can still feel a little warmness in the heel that tells me if I wear them any longer, I will get blisters again. And sometimes I can tell my toes are starting to go numb.

I feel like these were a big waste of money for me. On my trip, I walked over ten miles, and these suckers are still not 'broken in.' I don't think they ever will be. Two stars because I like the leather and the eco-friendly nature of the materials.if I wear them any longer, I will get blisters again. And sometimes I can tell my toes are starting to go numb.

column6: Baggallini Messenger Bagg
column14:
First, let me start by saying, this bag is so close to perfect it is painful for me to give it 3 stars. I was looking for something that would function as a purse for me and mini-diaper bag for my toddler's stuff. This bag is great - it fits my wallet and various purse stuff, his diaper changing pad from SkipHop, I can fit his Thermos funtainer in the side mesh pocket, and the other pocket fits my iPhone 6, plus I have room for more - I often carry snacks, extra wipes, small toys, etc.! And even with all this room, the bag doesn't seem huge or bulky. The material is great, resistant to stains, the blue color is vibrant, the zippers are comfortable and zip nicely...it's awesome.

Here's the problem. I'm 5'2", and the bag just will NOT stay in place on my back. If I shift or squat down, the whole bag rotates around off my back and ends up under my left arm near my hip. Once that meant it ended up in a water play table I was standing at with my son (although luckily the water resistant material kept my stuff dry). The strap needs a grip material or something, or the straps need to be shorter? The constant sliding around to the front also chafes my neck. The metal buckles that hold the straps to the length you want also let the straps come loose easily. If there was a way to convert this to a traditional backpack with two straps, my life would be amazing and I'd have no complaints whatsoever.

It's the perfect bag except for the huge flaw, the frustration of the crossbody strap is enough to make me not want to use it, but the functionality, space, and quality of the rest of the bag keeps me struggling with it. It's honestly a fine line right now. A true love/hate relationship.

column14:
This purse is the most precious purse ever. I love it so much.

It's like, not huge like a mom purse but at the same time it's not a tiny useless coin purse. I can put all kinds of junk in here and it fits perfectly. It's also really soft and high quality, which is great. I was kind of shocked at how inexpensive it is for such a good thing, but that's probably because it's made of fake leather‚Äînot that I mind.

The top zipper is nice and snug and hasn't slipped, though the bag isn't rain-safe or anything. In addition, there's a nice pouch on the back side of it that zips well. Inside the bag, there's two little pouches that're perfect for holding cards or a small wallet or your phone, and it also has a zip pocket on the other side of the purse that's a bit bigger. I almost immediately broke the zipper on that inner pouch, though... I have that issue with every purse though, not just this one, so I'm not sure if it's just that I'm dumb and break zippers a lot or that inside-purse zippers are just really fallible for some reason.

column13: Solid shoe, tighter fit than normal Jungle Mocs
column14: Like all the Merrell Jungle Mocs, these are well-made and durable shoes. Unfortunately, Merrell chose to make these Ventilator model shoes on a different last than the standard Jungle Mocs...these are narrower, slightly straighter from heel to toe, and not as deep in the forefoot so the net result is a smaller, tighter fit. I wear an 11D in the normal Jungle Mocs and the same size in the Ventilator model is tight enough to be distinctly uncomfortable after a couple hours...not sure I'll even be able to wear these enough to break them in and see if they stretch out. Merrell, if you're listening, please make sure you build your shoes on the same last, to the same dimensions for each size/width!

column14: So this is my very first product review EVER! For months now I had been debating whether or not to purchase these boots. I bought a few different pairs of cowboy boots from other sites and it turned out to either not be what I expected or the boot ends up not fitting (too big). Most reviews recommend "sizing up" for cowboy boots. That's what I did on my previous purchases and the shoe was too big so I decided to stick to my regular shoe size for these. I ordered a size 8. The boot is ok. I like the style, heel is perfect. They feel ok, but they have that "distressed" look that I'm not too much a fan of. They look used. My right foot fit perfect but the left I couldn't even get my foot in. I've never had an issue with any of my shoes fitting differently so it's definitely the boot. It's the best deal I found on the Internet for a pair of cowboy boots so I can't really complain. I will order a 1/2 size up hoping they will fit better. 4 starts for this product: the price is good, the shipping speed was terrific!  Got them literally the next day with free standard shipping. The 2 things taking away the 5th star was the worn look and the left boot not fitting.

column13: FOR THE PRICE, they are great...FOR THE PRICE!
column14:
I was looking for something casual enough to wear with jeans but dressy enough to wear if I decide to throw on a jacket. These boots fit the bill. I read the review and generally agree with all of them. These are $100 boots. I don't expect the workmanship, quality, durability or comfort to be within a thousand miles of Fryes or Allen Edmonds. If you are expecting that, buy Fryes or Allen Edmonds! These are "fashion boots" plain and simple. They look good and they fit over your feet, that's it.

My initial impression of the leather was not great. I definitely had that pleather look and feel. But, one treatment with some Leather Honey and it softened right up and took on a much deeper, richer color. I'll keep them soaked in it until they break in.

There is no cushioning or support in these boots. Tried pulling some insoles out of a pair of Sperry's I had near by but the toe box is too tight to be able to add them. I'm not saying they are uncomfortable in any way, but they aren't something you are going to want to go hiking in.

They run really big. I wear 11.5 sneakers. I bought these boots in 11 and there is still plenty of room in front of the toe. I probably could go with a 10.5 but I'm not going to bother sending them back, the 11 is fine.

I'm not really sure about the sole. The rubbery bottom is a bit cheesy looking and I've read it doesn't hold up. Frankly, part of me hopes it wears out. I'll just run it over to the cobbler and have him put a better looking, better performing sole on for me. It's cheap and easy so no worries there.

If you like the look and style, want something between dress and casual and understand that they are just basic boots, you'll be happy with these.

column13: She Keens In Sorrow Over The Loss of a GREAT Water Shoe...
column14: I have several pair of Venice H2 sandals that I use for aquatic exercise at the gym.  I've had them for a couple of years and though they are still quite sturdy, they are really faded.  So I decided to get some new ones and I thought the Celestial Blue was very pretty.  I am very sad to report that I had to return them though.  These were not nearly as roomy as the older Venice H2s.  In fact, I couldn't get my foot all the way into them even after several minutes struggling.  To be 100% fair, these are not sold as a wide shoe and I DO have a very wide foot with a high instep just to make matters a little worse.  However, Keens of the past fit me beautifully, and folks with normal feet could easily cinch up the bungee for a more snug fit.  The reason for one star deduction is the inconsistency of the fit, not because of quality.  As I said, the current shoes I own have served me well, and will continue to do so even though they don't look as bright as they once did.  I don't know what the heck I am going to do when I HAVE to replace them.  I really wish Keen would carry some wide style options.

column6: Skechers Performance Men's Go Golf Bionic Golf Shoe
column14: Sketchers shoes, like many brands made abroad, are hit or miss with their sizing.  I wear 8.5 and even in stores find same shoe and size fit differently. In general, I have found Sketcher's can run a quarter to half size small, thus take lots of breaking in. I have tried going half size larger, but foot seems to swim in the show.  I have used several models of Sketcher street shoes with gripping soles as my golf shoe of choice for 15 years. Discovering these specialty golf shoes at almost half the price in local golf stores, I took the chance and violated my long standing rule of never buying shoes online and unfitted. They remain tight, especially in the vamp and uppers. Toe space is adequate and length is good, but like other Sketchers, they run smaller than actual sizing, requiring extra toil and discomfort to break in. The quality of shoe seems solid, with minimal exposed stitching. If the soles wear out, as others have complained, will use for yard work. Wish they had a heal strap or bit higher heal collar, but they are good looking shoe. Advise ordering half size large than you may be used to.

column13: Caveat Emptor: Sizing is way off.
column14: Ok. The shoes are very cool - in both senses of that word. And if they fit, I suspect they would be very comforable. But the sizing business is utterly ridiculous. I wear a European 44. In some shoes (including my first KEEN shoes, a 43 is a better fit. I read the warnings that they run small, and took the advice to go up a half size. I ordered 45, and they fit like sausage casings and cut off circulation.  I suspect that even 46 might be too snug. NB; This is not just  a question of width. The 45s are barely long enough. If you are able to send shoes back and forth until you get the right fit, then go for it. These are a great design. (I live overseas, so can't swap until I get my size.) KEEN should really work out the true measurement of each of the UNEEK sizes and sell people the size they need. Throw a note int he box to tell people to ignore the size printed on the shoes.

column6: Designer Inspired Quilted Crossbody Bag
column13: Cute purse, love the metal link strap!
column14:
This is a cute, classy little bag for a small price. The faux leather fabric is quilted and soft, it doesn't feel cheaply made. The metal medallion on the front adds interest, though I think I'd like it more if it was less abstract. From a distance it looks sort of like a tree. The purse is small but capable of holding all the essentials like your phone, lipstick, credit cards, etc. Perfect for a dressy night out when you don't want to haul a bigger bag around. My favorite part is the extra long crossbody strap, which is a strip of the purse fabric woven through metal links. The chances of this purse strap breaking are tiny! One issue I had is that I ordered the red color. The color in person is somewhat red but has a very dark brown tone. It's darker than the photo and definitely not a bright pop of red. I still do like it and think it will get plenty of use.

I have received free products to help facilitate my review but all opinions are my own.

column6: LeSportsac Deluxe Everyday Bag Shoulder Bag
column14:
[[VIDEOID:963645424e75760b2565eecc40f84c71]]I purchased this bag in March 2013. I have used it as my everyday handbag for about 2.5 years, and it still looks brand new!

If you want a bag to help keep you organized, look no further. This bag has several sections, all with zipper closures:
-Two separate main compartments
-One interior pouch in the front main compartment
-One removable pouch
-Two small exterior compartments on the front of the bag
-One large exterior compartment on the back of the bag

That's seven places to store your stuff! And . . . if you need just a little extra room, you can unzip the zipper on the bottom of the front main compartment to expand the bag. That gives you even more room for even more stuff! (Though, I prefer the look of the bag in its condensed mode and have never used the \\\expansion pack.\\\\\" :))

The bag itself is made of nylon, and consequently, it is lightweight. I actually purchased this bag because my traditional faux leather purse was a burden on my shoulder. It was heavy, even without any contents. This LeSportsac bag was a refreshing change. When completely empty, the bag weighs approximately 12.5 ounces. So, the bag really is only as heavy as you want it to be. Although, if you find the bag to be too heavy on your shoulder after a long day of shopping, simply adjust the strap and wear it as a crossbody bag.

The tag inside my bag indicates you can wash it by hand in cold water and then hang it to dry. However, it warns that fading may occur during washing. It also states you should not iron the bag or use bleach or detergent. I have never attempted to wash my bag, but I did have a very unfortunate incident shortly after purchasing it. You don't need all of the details, but let's just say a piece of a peanut butter cup melted onto the exterior of my bag. I spot-cleaned the area with excellent results. As previously mentioned, my bag still looks brand new. (With the exception of that peanut butter cup, I actually do take very good care of my belongings. :))

The main disadvantage of this bag is that it's pretty casual and might not be appropriate for all occasions. It's a very well-branded bag. \\\\\"LeSportsac\\\\\" is printed on all of the zipper pulls and in succession on the strap and on the trim on the front and back of the bag. I purchased my bag in black to use as an everyday handbag, and as an added bonus, the LeSportsac branding isn't quite as visible on the black version as it is on other prints.

This has been a durable bag for me, and I have not had any issues with it. It makes a great organizational bag for daily use, and it is perfect for travel. I think you'll tire of the bag before the bag wears out on you. When that happens, simply remove your belongings and collapse the bag for easy storage.he exception of that peanut butter cup, I actually do take very good care of my belongings. :))

column6: Salomon Men's Speedcross 3 Trail Running Shoe
column13: Extremely light and fit my feet like a glove
column14:
I would rate these shoes in 3 different categories.
1) Fit and Comfort = 5 Stars. Extremely light and fit my feet like a glove. Often I forget that I have them on.
2) Performance = 4 Stars. Great traction when new but the shoe is a little narrow which can lead to rolling your ankle. I would also like a little more cushioning to protect joints during hikes/runs.
3) Durability = 3 Stars. The soles simply wear out too fast. If you walk or run on any kind of pavement you can literally watch the soles wear after each outing. I understand this shoe is meant for trails but many people will occasionally wear them on a paved surface which will quickly lead to tread wear.
So overall I would rate these shoes 4 Stars.

column6: Baggallini Roundabout Bagg
column13: A few stitches came loose before I even took off the tags
column14:
Some stitches came loose (on the rear zipper compartment) before I even got a chance to take off the tags, weep ...

Pros:
- light colored lining
- the myriad of compartments are good for organizing small flat objects (band-aids, tiny eye-drop bottles, ..)
- internal organization in the middle compartment

Cons:
- stitches came loose while purse was still NEW
- shoulder strap too narrow to wear comfortably
- no quick access / drop-in pockets for keys or phone
- compartments are no good for anything with thickness. Say, a flat camera by itself is okay, but not with a minimally padded case -- it will overstuff the bag
- front and back zippered compartments are identical. If they were different I won't have to open both to find things
- no pen holder
- no organization in the front and back zippered compartments. For such a small bag all the little things roll to the bottom
- rear slip pocket is rarely in use except to hold a tissue, or a pen

column6: Nine West Women's Valcaria Riding Boot
column14: . . . especially of women's clothing items. Who knows, maybe the boot varies a lot and that leads to all these conflicting reports about how it fits. I'm betting it has more to do with the fact that women sometimes blame the clothes for not fitting them, without explaining how their (highly individual) body measurements may have had something to do with the fit. I'm 5'2", 130 pounds (I have a small waist and carry most of my weight in T&a but I have shapely/average calves), and while my foot is technically a 5.5 wide, I can usually get away with a 6 regular. I took a chance on this boot, and I regret it.  The toe box pinches. Not a big problem, it's a leather boot and there are ways to fix that. Don't expect them to fit out of the box, though.  The real problem is that my legs rattle around in the shaft of this boot like the clapper in a bell, and that's harder to fix. I have to stuff my jeans and wear wool socks, and the end result is still unflattering because it makes my legs look shorter and chubbier than they are. I'm simultaneously not tall enough, not skinny enough, and not heavy enough to make these work.  Shipping for returns doesn't make it worth my while to return the boots, so I'll try and sell them for at least what I paid for them and keep trying.

column13: These lenses rose tint my world.
column14:
I love the way these looked the moment I opened the box. I purchased the Transparent Red version of the glasses. The arms are attached to the frames with screws, not pins, and are about 5 inches in length. The nose pieces are a clear soft plastic and the temple tips are covered with black plastic to keep you from getting scratched. If things get loose, or you lose a nosepad, you should be fine with average repair kit. The frames are designed to comfortably fit the curve of your face. Everything about these sunglasses scream classic aviator, and then you get to the lenses.

Set inside the bright silver frame, the vibrant red lenses really stand out. To me, the color very reminiscent of the red side of a pair of older style 3d glasses. I've usually only seen this color of a lens, while shopping in the toy or party sections of my local store. Fortunately, these aren't just toy sunglasses. The non-polarized lenses are rated at absorbing 99% of the UVA and UVB spectrums, which are they ones they blame for premature aging and cataracts, among other things. You can wear these sunglasses without sacrificing look for protection. Put these on, and see the world in a whole new view. I was lucky enough to receive this product at a discount for my honest and unbiased review.

column6: Air Balance Women Black/Fuchsia Hiking Boots
column14: I LOVE these boots.  I hike ALOT.  Therefore I need something that is going to last and gives good arch support.  Now, I know that getting good arch support is at a premium these days so I was all prepared to have to go get arch support inserts.  I don't have to.  Surprisingly enough.  I wanted something 'fun' so I decided on these for their color.  yay.  Are these the best built hiking boots I have ever worn? No.  But I didn't pay $185.00 for them either.  Love the tread too...great hiking over rocks.  One thing to 'complain' about? The soles are a bit thin.  I can feel sharp rocks through the soles...but on the plus side.. I can feel the ground thru the soles too..so over rough terrain..that's a plus.  I really like these boots and would purchase them again.  NOTE>>>>  these are NOT heavy duty.  These are...head up the trail for a day hike kind of boot where rocks, sticks and creeks are going to be part of the deal.  If you are going to go on an extreme trek over a few days.. these might not be what you would want as the soles are (in my opinion) a bit thin and your feet might be hurting at the end of day two.  Think heavy duty tennis shoes not steel toed hiking boots.  :)

column13: I love these boots!! They are very pretty and well-made!! I ordered the black/red.
column14:
THE FIT
These boots do run a size too big, just as the other reviews stated. Thanks to the reviews, I ordered a size 9. I wear a size 9.5-10 .. regular (no letter next to the letter) .. or B(M) as some other manufactures label their shoes. I put on a pair of thick, reinforced men's socks to try them on .. that is the ONLY reason they fit a little tight around my right foot, which is bigger than my left. I like how the point is not overwhelmingly long .. like some pointed shoes which cause you to trip and the toe to bend against the end of your toes. They do have a tap sound, but it's a solid low-base sound .. not like my other cowboy boots .. you can hear me walking from about 20 feet away with those on. I finally feel like I have a real pair of cowboy boots ..so far as look, feel, and craft are concerned.

STYLE
As I stated in my title, I LOVE THESE BOOTS .. they are very pretty! They also have a professional, serious look to them as well. The boots look exactly like the picture, even down to the color!! The red on the toes looks darker than the picture inside, but outside in the sun it's exactly the same red .. that's just a little side info .. just in case one of the reasons you're considering buying them is because of the brightness of the red on the toes. That was one of my reasons. They came a day early. I am very excited to wear them with my outfit!! I immediately ran to the closet for a pair of socks and the top half of my outfit!! I am very tempted to order them in black/beige!

column6: BOBS from Skechers Women's Keepsakes Winter Wonder Memory-Foam Slipper
column14:
Sketchers are usually a bit narrow for me, and these slippers are no exception. That said, I don't mind a nice snug slipper, but there are a few other reasons I wasn't thrilled with these.
Pros:
- expensive look and feel of the outer leather and sole
- could easily be passed off as shoes with the right pair of jeans
- tall platform sole means more insulation from the cold floor and a bit of height, much appreciated if you're short like me
- no annoying part behind the heel
Cons:
- memory foam? perhaps... but these do not have the comfort and support usually associated with that description
- gigantic hard sole means indoor wear is limited to walking around; these seem better suited to the outdoors than curling up on the couch
- there's a nice big scratchy tag sewn in right where the heel sits
- the faux fur is a bit long and uncomfortably itchy inside the slipper, and always finds its way between my toes; yes it's warm, but it feels plastic-y and annoying (if you have a narrow foot, socks are recommended)

These will be kept by the back door for short trips outside during cold weather, but with limited comfort and indoor usefulness, these are overall quite a disappointment.

column6: ALLROUNDER by MEPHISTO Women's Niro Mary Jane Flat
column13: The upper is the only good part.
column14: I walk dogs, and have collected a lot of "comfort" shoes in red to go with my business color. Last year I broke my leg and the hospital cut off my Keen Venice H2 that I was wearing for the first time, and that color has been discontinued(!) I was tired of Keens but can't find shoes as good other than Ahnus that fit my foot and support a lot of walking. I got these Allrounder Niro mesh-style on sale, and expected that at least they would have the foundation of an average gym shoe. The upper is perfectly nice, but if you do buy them, you will need to replace the paper-thin insoles with something that costs as much as another pair of shoes. The insole needs to provide all the cushioning/shock absorption you won't have, heel cups for stability and an arch support. I didn't get these through Amazon, but they sure seem like a knock-off, or Mephisto's reputation is over.

column6: 5.11 Men's Taclite 8\ Boot"
column13: Great for medium or light duty.
column14: I give 4 of 5. I bought in April and have used these boots to an extreme. With the suede, the boot is all-around lighter, which makes it high quality for medium or light duty activity.  Within the first week, the side holes "ports" were damaged of their screen, while running in the woods. One recently ripped out, not sure why. When you first put them on, you'll be amazed. I have high arches and immediately felt comfortable. Very small break in period as I became accustomed to the boot height.  I was afraid of getting them wet at first, but discovered they held up well I everything below the top of the toe. Water above would get in the boot, but eventually dry out. Water also affects its bright color and makes it dark, even after drying.  I get compliments on my boots all the time. They are awesome, but some minor issues need attention before they can get 5 out of 5 from me. I will definitely buy another pair soon.  Update: It has been 13 months since purchase and the eyelets are just starting to fail at the tops of the boots. I've worn these boots nearly everyday since purchase. They've stood up well for being a light weight boot. I'll be buying another pair shortly, but will keep wearing these until they are nothing but dust.

column13: Awesome running shoes with zero drop.
column14:
I transitioned from the Merrell Ascend Glove and further back than that, the Trail Glove. The Virrata is the exact shoe I was looking for. I love the zero drop, and that is all I need. I want proper running form, but I don't need to be "feeling the road." That part of running is overrated. The Merrell gloves are nice, but these are better. The cushion is enough for me to run further without feeling really much of any pain and they are extremely light. Lightest shoes I've ever worn.

They are probably not very good for trails because of a lack of sole tread, but for road running, they are it.

column6: Chaco Men's Cabrera Flip Sandal
column14:
I first ordered size 13 (size 49 Euro - which is a little larger than standard shoe sizing for US 13). Upon receiving them, I noticed they fit like a size 12 US. I looked and found the sticker on the sandal said size 46 Euro, which is smaller than standard shoe sizing for US 13. Amazon seamlessly returned the sandals at their expense, and had my new pair of size 14 US (which fit exactly like 13's) at my doorstep within two days!

That being said, what about the quality? Well, I couldn't be more pleased. I purchased these as an alternative to the typical $30-40 leather/fabric sandals I buy and wear out within a few months. I was hoping they would be something that would last longer than one year.

The leather is obviously durable, and the stitching appears to be of a very high quality. Time will tell, of course, but first impressions place these sandals in a much higher quality tier than your typical shoe store options. The arch support is fantastic and the sandal seems to somewhat wrap around the edge of my foot very comfortably. The rubber sole looks like it will have a lot of life before wearing out. They are a bit narrow for me, but I do have wide feet. The only difference I might note (not really a complaint), is that they are a much more firm sandal than typical store-bought options. Within a few days, I'm noticing that they are breaking in and forming to the shape of my foot ever so slightly, making them more comfortable each time I wear them! Even though they are firm, I do not seem to have any trouble wearing them for long hours without discomfort. They seem like they will continue to grow in comfort as they wear.

I purchased the Otter color, and am very pleased with the design. The color is a good bit darker brown than the photo, but I also anticipate natural fading/wear in the leather over time.

Overall, I highly recommend this product! The Chaco brand was referred to me by a friend, and it sure made a believer out of me! I anticipate years of use from this product, not months - you won't be disappointed ;)

[[ASIN:B00KXD998S Chaco Men's Cabrera Flip Sandal, Otter, 13 M US]]

column6: JD Fisk Men's Gilby Oxford
column13: Somebody at JD Fisk is completely crazy!!  And I'm glad.
column14:
Somebody at JD Fisk is completely crazy!! The price of these shoes is astoundingly low. Do they know they're giving their product away?Come to think of it, maybe I should buy a few more of these and THEN alert them to what's going on. Hopefully they won't read this.
I ordered the black version for $19.99 and held my breath to receive it - thinking it was going to be awful. It is soooo not. I still cannot understand how this quality can be sold at these prices.

Fit & comfort
Exactly as expected. I ordered size 11 and it fit exactly as all my other size 11s. For comfort, lets remember that this is an oxford. It does have firm areas which give its shape and rigidity. For those buying this as an upgrade from loafers you will find it more firm (as you would for any quality oxford). But for office-types like myself who are accustomed to wearing oxfords this shoe will be fine for all day wear.

Build quality
The leather lining is supple and rich. I uploaded a photo which I hope conveys how rich. The insole is deep and cushy. The outsole is smooth and true. The tooling and overall finish are top notch.

Sole
I see a number of reviews arguing whether the sole is or isn't leather. I am now satisfied that it is NOT leather. It is a very dense, very thick synthetic rubber that I suspect will wear very well over time. It is extremely hard and I can see how, even some purchasers, could mistake it for leather, but it isn't. Again, that's not an issue for me. I believe it will hold up well over the years.

Color
One thing to point out that you won't see from the pictures: These shoes are not completely black!! It is a deep grey, maybe slate. Only the heel and toe are fully black. But, as in the pictures on Amazon this can definitely pass as black. It's not an issue for me - it's actually a bonus for me as it gives me options. It makes the shoe slightly different from my other black shoes. Note that the difference in shade is only very slight - definitely not a two-tone - merely a very deep grey misted with black at the heel and toes. Beautiful effect!! I imagine if you wanted it all black then dye or shoe polish would be an easy solution - but it's fine for me. In fact, I think I'll use neutral polish (rather than black) in order to keep the effect. Most of your shoe's admirers won't even notice it - and believe me you will have plenty of admirers when wearing these.

Value
It is a bit crazy to be commenting on value after owning this shoe for such a short period. So I admit that I cannot speak about durability but the build quality, style and finish place the value of this shoe in the $90-$120 range.

CONCLUSION

column13: Comfortable, Convenient Slip-On Shoes (while they last)
column14: I owned an earlier version of this shoe, bought from an outlet store, but it seems this is only available online via Amazon or Skechers direct now.  These are more comfortable than the prior version, however the outer material doesn't seem to be of the same quality; seems a bit more styrofoam-like than faux-suede, but unless you're closely examining the shoe, it's a bit hard to tell.  The one problem this shoe has in common with the prior version is also that the insole/sock liner is glued into the shoe, so if you have orthotics, you'll have to tediously rip out the liner, which comes off in chunks, rather than one piece.  Still, it's a great slip-on shoe for quick entry/exits if you're frequently going out and don't want to be bothered with laces (if you don't wear shoes inside your home).  UPDATE:  I previously rated this as 4 stars, but have changed it to 2 stars.  The prior version of the shoe was more durable, lasted longer and held up better. This updated version seemed to start disintegrating after about five months of by no means heavy use, only to do errands/shopping.  The upper material is not of the same quality and began to look really rough.  The tread on the soles wore down to almost nothing.  It's a shame they didn't last as long as the prior version did, and the older ones were more heavily used.

column6: Women's Fashion Polarized Sunglasses, Oversized and Vintage Style by Coleman
column13: These sunglasses look great and cut glare like a boss
column14:
I'll admit that I have the tendency to lose or break sunglasses, so I tend to just grab cheap ones that I'm not afraid of hurting. For years I've heard how much polarized sunglasses can help and I decided to finally bite the bullet.

The amount of glare that these sunglasses cuts is phenomenal. I live in Southern USA and it gets bright down here sometimes. I'm now able to see the road when I'm driving so much better than I could with my old sunglasses, and this is important to me as I usually have my little boys in the car with me.

The size and look of these is also fabulous. I love big sunglasses and these actually make me feel confident when I'm wearing them. They look like they're a lot more expensive than they are so you can look stylish and save a little money too.

Let's just say that I'm going to be a lot more careful with these than I have with my past sunglasses!!

**I received the Coleman Oversized and Vintage Women's Polarized Sunglasses for a discounted price in return for my honest and unbiased review. All opinions are 100% my own and no further compensation was received.

column14: Soooo disappointed. They sounded perfect. I have loved Sanuk yoga mat flip flops for a couple years now and have several pairs. column6: Tosbuy Men's and Women's Slip on Water Shoes,beach Aqua,hiking,surfing,running Sneakers
column14:
I used these shoes for the first time during a full day at Xplor in Mexico that included walking on flat and inclined wet and dry concrete, swimming, and driving ATVs.

Durability - 2/5 stars - The heel of the shoes is already starting to wear apart where the collar surrounds your foot. I have concerns over the pull cord eventually breaking and wonder if the shoes will become unusable if it breaks.
Fit - 4/5 stars - Comfortable all day long with no blistering or chafing. Adjustable pull cord works well to secure shoes to your feet, but can get annoying since it swings around and occasionally goes under feet when walking.
Traction - 1/5 stars - On wet surfaces these shoes make you feel like you're walking on ice. They're fine on dry land, but avoid these if you plan to be walking on anything smooth and wet outside of water.

Overall I'd probably be inclined to look to Speedo or another brand without the pull cord and with better grip. As others have mentioned, these are definitely not shoes I'd wear hiking, surfing, or running.
