column6: Vivobarefoot Women's 200040 Slingback Sandal
column14:
I've had these sandals in the teal for about half a year now and they have become my favorite pair of sandals. Initially I had a hard time getting the got just right, but they have now loosened and conformed better to my foot so I can just slide in and out with no problems. Until they were broken in they also cut into my heel uncomfortably. This is no longer a problem and may have just been fixed by finding the perfect spot to adjust the slider between the toes.

I have used these sandals for everyday walking, running, and hiking trails. The bottom rubber had good grip, but on sloped surfaces and damp feet you slide sideways out of the shoe.

After many miles of wear including rocky trails, salt water and river crossings the sole of the shoe is showing zero wear. One sandal is starting to separate the foot pad from the rubber, but I think I can easily fix this. The left side is showing no separation and I think the damage has been caused by a slightly bum leg making me catch and fold the front of the sandal under my foot occasionally.

I have wide feet and am an experienced minimalist runner. Don't get this sandal is you want a soft cushy ride. This is basically a minimally padded chunk of tire rubber strapped to your foot. I can't compare this sandal to other similar hurache designs, but I'm happy enough with mine that I plan to buy another pair or two in case I can't buy replacements in the future.

column6: PUMA Men's Touring Cat Mercedes Grid Motorsport Fashion Sneaker
column14:
I've been buying Puma sport shoes, on and off, since I bought a pair of soccer shoes in 1959. I have a C width foot and they always fit perfectly.

These "sneakers" could not fit me better. I bought them for driving shoes and they have a stiff, non-slip, sole which is ideal for that. They also have a rounded heel excellent for driving.The sole is fairly thin, has little cushioning, and very little tread pattern, so I don't know how useful they would be as all-purpose "Sneakers"

The only con is the side could be cut a little lower under the ankles. They rub a bit on me. I deducted a star for that.

3/22/16: I added back the star because the shoes have broken in and are some of the most comfortable shoes I've ever worn (in 72 years)! However, I wore them one day walking on gravel paths and they were as sensitive (uncomfortable) as I suspected they'd be. For driving and walking on sidewalks they are superb.

column14: I received the package and upon opening my house was filled with a noxious smell of new tire and a horrid chemical compound. My wife ordered me to put them outside or in the garage. I looked up information on the internet about the issue. Apparently, these faux leathers produced in China (especially) have a terrible odor. Numerous web pages found on Google give direction on how to reduce the smell--none offered the possibility of complete removal. So far, I have used dishwashing soap, window cleaning spray, white vinegar mixed with water and wrapped them in newspaper with tissue wrapped charcoal placed inside the shoe. The odor persists. The last resort is to put them in a bag with charcoal (or Odoreaters) for two weeks. That's my next and last attempt. If I have no success, I will return them prior to deadline.

column13: If the shoe fits wear it - however, you might like it's cousin the Voyager better.
column14: I've worn the Taghee before and been totally satisfied, however, the pair I just purchased seems markedly narrower than previous purchases. Overall it's an excellent shoe but they seem to be running narrower now, and the fact is that you really do need to order a half size larger, which I did.  In my mind it's a bit of a red flag when a company can't produce a shoe that's true to size. I've never experienced the quality failures many speak about with any KEEN shoes falling apart, but the sizing is an issue.  I have purchased a pair of KEEN Voyagers directly from KEEN and I will say that if you love KEEN's and sizing is of concern that is the shoe to buy. It offers a generous foot bed, 5 pair of lace up loops - Targhee only has 4 - it fits a bit higher on the ankle though it is truly a low cut hiking shoe and it is most certainly 'true to size'. The thing about the 5 pair of lace loops is that it provides better adjustment to allow wearing a variety of sock weights and properly support your foot.

column6: Adidas Ladies Adistar Boost Running Shoes (UK 8/US 9.5/EUR 42)
column13: Oasics are also great but for persons with narrow-er feet and not necessarily ...
column14: It took me a while to write this review and in fact the only reason I am writing it is because there were no reviews when I made my purchase. The seller has to be commended for their packing style and delivery speed; I received the shoes in a matter of days and I didn't have to grit my teeth whilst ripping through wasteful or inappropriate packaging.  I own a lot of shoes and grew up wearing Addidas - the shoes were always well constructed and the fit and comfort were a runner's dream but the color choices were lacking so I switched to Oasics. Oasics are also great but for persons with narrow-er feet and not necessarily narrow feet. However, I strongly believe that Addidas are still better for me and I've experimented with a great number of brands, regardless of cost for the goal of 'fit'.  I was pleasantly surprised with these shoes. The quality has not changed thankfully and these shoes feel like walking on clouds. My only complaint is about the sizing. I normally wear a 9.5(B)M and this is shoe is quite unforgiving because of the stretch-like fabric which is good for ventilation but quickly shows that I should have ordered a half size bigger. So for those of you looking for a new shoe, this is it but be sure to order a half size up.

column13: Great shoe but wide is not-so-wide
column14: This shoe is VERY comfortable to wear...with one exception.  I ordered the wide size and, for a wide it's, well, not.  They will break-in a little wider, but out of the box, it feels only marginally wider than a medium.  Since it's basically impossible to find this in the stores, I tried other brands before buying this.  The Moab Ventilator from Merrell, for example, has enough room to fit a small army in.  I own a pair of Timberland White Ledge in non-wide and these are only marginally wider than the White Ledges.  It's not enough to make me want to return them, but I wish the wide was definitely a little wider.  Outside of that exception, it's one of the most comfortable pairs of shoes I've ever worn.  It is super comfortable on the bottom of my feet.  The shoe is high-quality and very stylish as well.  I definitely recommend these, but if you have really wide feet, you may want to consider the Moab Ventilators - though they are lower quality and frankly really ugly.  There is also a version of these same shoes with Gore-Tex if you want the waterproofing - though there are complaints on Amazon's listing of those being really narrow, perhaps more so than these are.  The Gore-Tex version is more money than these.

column13: and would not recommend this as a durable winter boot
column14: I ordered these a half size up (I normally wear 7.5, went for 8) so I could wear these with thicker socks. I haven't had a chance to wear them in harsher weather but some things to note for future buyers: this is less of a "black" combat boot and more of a very, very dark grey. The difference is hardly noticeable, and I actually prefer it so it's not as harsh - the material on the outside is also a lot softer than I expected. The interior is lined with a furry/shearling-like material which definitely makes this a warm boot. I don't expect these to last longer than 2 Fall/Winter seasons in Seattle weather, and would not recommend this as a durable winter boot. BUT, it is still very comfortable and I think if you're interested in buying a combat boot to try, this would be a good place to start.

column6: Red Wing Heritage Iron Ranger 6-Inch Boot
column14:
I eventually returned these because they were significantly too large. I am giving them five stars because of the boot itself. not my poor sizing choice. I got the correct size from the red wing store and they are the best pair of boots i have ever owned. hands down. The only thing to be weary of is the sizing. Its jank. I wear a size 11 in vans classics and 11 1/5 in nike frees and I eventually ended up with a size 10 in these. TEN. They fit perfectly. If I put them up to my roommates size 11 justin boots they are the same length. crazy. here are a few tips to consider when buying iron rangers:
1: assume the red wing salesmen is an idiot and has never put a pair of shoes on in his life. from what I've gathered and from personal experience they always size you way larger than you need. Do not be afraid to ask for three or four different sizes to try on. no matter how dumb of a look he gives you. you are shelling out three hundo on some leather. be damn sure its right.
2: they are supposed to be tight when you are first wearing them. don't worry about that. the tongue fold pressed so hard on the top of my foot when I first wore them out of the store that I had a bruise. 2 days later it was totally bearable and a week later it was non existent. in short, these cow sacks stretch. and its awesome.
3: to break them in quicker take your boot and massage and move the portion of leather that is the tightest a good bit. you will notice it will significantly soften the leather.
4: after buying, lace up, pimp walk, find babes.

column6: Arnette Quick Draw AN4178 Wrap Polarized Sunglasses
column13: Another Great Pair of Sunglasses from Arnette
column14: I have owned several pairs of Arnette sunglasses and I have never been disappointed with them. Lens and frame quality are very good. I always stick with polarized lenses on my sunglasses unless I'm looking for photochromatic types. The polarizing quality of Arnette lenses seems to be better than many brands I have tried. When Arnette says you are buying a wrap-around frame, be prepared for real wrap-around style. My favorite Arnette model has always been the Raven, but I thought I would give the Quickdraw a try. Glad I did. The fit for me is perfect. The sunglasses sit perfectly level on my face. This may sound weird to some, but I have experience with some sunglasses that just always feel like they are sitting crooked on my face. Drives me crazy with constant adjustments. Maybe my ears are crooked?  Peripheral vision is a bit obscured by the thickness of the frame, but this has not been an issue for me. They come with a nice case, lens cloth, and a fabric bag for storage. Recommended. Jimmy

column6: Reebok Men's Crossfit Sprint TR Training Shoe
column13: So far, so good.  Primarily going to use these at the gym.
column14: I'm used to buying running shoes.  Night and day difference.  However, these crossfit shoes are quite comfortable as general purpose gym shoes.  The fit is good (my foot is kind of narrow).  There is not as much lift at the heel as I have on my running shoes, which I think is a plus when doing squats and other leg exercises.  The foam on the sole seems sturdier, or maybe just a bit more firm than what I am accustomed to with running shoes.  I don't think I would take them out and run 5-10 miles, but given the cushioning that most of the treadmills at our gym provide, I have not had any issues with jogging 2-3 miles in these on the treadmill.  It's been quite a few years since buying a pair of Reebok shoes, but the build quality appears decent and hopefully these will hold up for some time.

column13: I love love love it, except for one small issue. (Issue now CORRECTED)
column14: ***ORIGINAL REVIEW (8/11/2015)*** OK, this is going to be an interesting review..... So from the product itself, I love love love it. Cutest thing ever. We are frequent Cruise travelers, and this year we are blessed with a baby boy, so we got these specifically for that intention (for him to wear on the ship). So this is all wonderful and I have no regrets. The only reason I am giving a 4 star instead of 5 stars is because when this item arrived, I noticed the left shoe side is labelled "6-9 month" and the right side is labelled "9-12 month". See pictures. Very bizzare. This is the first time ever happened to me. So I immediately took out my tape measure, and measured the length of the outsole, and they BOTH measured 4 7/8 inches, which confirms 9-12 months. Which kinda makes sense since when I look at them, they look exactly the same, and somewhat big for my baby right now.... So I think the labelling is just wrong, but the size is the same. So please please please, if you order this upon receiving it, DON'T assume the size is automatically correct, please check the size to make sure.  I purchased this item at a discount in exchange for an honest review. If you find this review helpful in any way at all, please click "yes" below (to find it helpful) to help me know what is helpful and keep at it. Thank you.  ***EDITED (8/12/2015)*** I was quite surprised, after I left my review yesterday, within hours the company reached out to me to apologize for their issue and that they want to make it up to me by sending me a replacement. This is superb customer service, especially with the fact that I did NOT reach out to them to inform I want my money back or replacement.... they did by themselves. Very satisfied, and changed my review now from 4 to 5 stars.

column13: Flattering, not as comfy as I hoped
column14:
I love Skechers but don't like lack of half size. I wear an 8 in the GoWalks but ordered a 9 based on reviews. An 8.5 would have been prefect.
These are cute and flattering. It's hard to find a sandal that is cut lower down to flatter the leg, more important in black.
I am not crazy about anything between my toes and generally avoid thong or toe ring styles.
I had some black adhesive ball-of-foot cushons I hoped would 1) pad the ball of foot for more comfort because this shoe has very little compared to most Skechers and 2) it would push my foot back for a better fit.
The pads really don't do much-might look for another pair and stack them, especially as the straps are stretching.
I do not think these are that comfortable. They are super lightweight but have very little padding in front.
My feet and legs hurt after 2-3 hrs of walking/shopping.
I do not wear heels.
I kept these because I needed this style, they are very flattering, are a reasonable wedge height, they don't make any noise like flipflops, they were a Lightning deal and they are lightweight.
I would not buy another pair of these.

column6: Womens Western Style Pure Color Handbag Shoulder Bag Black
column13: Make sure all fittings are on tight.
column14:
I must admit, I was quite impressed with this bag. Mine looked a tad bit different from the pictures in the listing. My zipper was not all black. It was gold. And there is a logo name on one side. See pics.

Perfect sized bag for my 13" macbook and files. The bag does not have feet so beware of putting it on the ground or "dragging" it. The straps are a nice length. It is long enough for me to wear on my shoulder and keep the bag tight against my body. Yet, short enough for me to hold it by the handles and walk with my arms down without dragging it on the floor. I'm 5'2".

The outer zipper pocket is big enough to hold my iphone 6 plus with wallet case (standing up). It's a bit of a tight squeeze if I try to lay it down completely inside the pocket. Any other smaller phone would fit much easier.

The interior has a nice lining that does not feel flimsy at all. There are multiple slip/open top pockets on both sides and one zippered pocket. It also has a nice long strap with lobster clip for holding your keys. I love this feature because I no longer have to dig for my keys as I walk to my car.

The bag material is synthetic leather and you can tell at first sight. It has a grainy texture and even smells like plastic. This bag has is well finished. Meaning, the straps, the stitching, etc is well done for a non name brand purse. There are a few stray strands of brown strings that I could see on the inside from the lining, but other than that, the straps did not have fraying. The stitching was nice and tight and the pockets were well sewn.

My favorite thing about this purse is its weight. It's VERY VERY light. I can't stand bags that weigh a lot when its empty. Add your stuff to it and you may as well skip the gym. I added pictures and everything you see in the one picture all fit inside the purse and I could zip it shut. Capacity is pretty good. The base/gusset is nice and wide.

Personally, I would pay about $25 tops for this purse just because it is not real leather. But as far as usability, practicality, and quality goes, this is a decent purse for those who don't care about name brands or the smell of leather.

My suggestions on how they can improve this purse:
Use a better zipper for the main compartment. The current zipper is a little sticky when opening and closing.
Add feet to the bottom of the bag.

I was provided a sample for my honest review.

UPDATE: 8/14/15
I've used this bag for less than a week on a daily basis. The gold nut that screws the strap onto the ring on the bag popped off. The pieces are not metal. They are painted to look like metal. Luckily it popped off when I was in my garage so I didn't lose that part. I managed to screw it back on and then made sure the other 3 were on tight. I'm a little worried now of putting my MacBook in here. So I only carry light things in the purse. I don't trust the straps anymore and don't want to risk destroying my computer.t real leather. column6: Crocs Women's Leigh Wedge Sandal
column14: I love these shoes!  They are so comfortable and I can't wait to get more colors! It is a little bit heathered and goes great with grey, navy, brown, jeans, etc.  I have a fair skin tone and don't do much tanning in the summer and the oat color looks much better with my fair skin than a bright white shoe.  The only problem I have had with these shoes is that they are very slick on wet surfaces.  I stepped on a little water in front of a drink machine and almost fell, but I would still highly recommend them!

column6: ASICS Men's GEL DS Trainer 20 Running Shoe
column13: It's a DS Trainer but Not a Good DS Trainer.
column14:
I like to review these Trainer's and this one is by far the worst DS Trainer I've bought on first usage. I've tried most all of them since about 2 or 3 and been wearing (running in) DS Trainers exclusively since 2003. Having said that, they are still an excellent shoe comparatively. I've been running in my DS 18's and then in these so I have a great side by side comparison.
Cons: Small fit. Tight toe box, which cramps the feet and takes awhile to break in. Top material takes a long time to break in and feel like a 29.99 shoe from big 5. Very aggressive heal compared to previous models. Tread pattern seems to allow for more slippage on dirt that the 18's.
Pros: Lighter than previous models. Good cushions. Normal DS Trainer feel.
Unknowns: Wear on sole (I only have about 25 miles and they look fine). Break in comfort (still haven't completely broken in)
After getting these, I wish I would have skipped this model and gone with the 19's.

column6: Adidas Ultra Boost Women's Running Shoes
column14:
I have been wearing these shoes on training runs for about three weeks now. The runs typically are from about 4 to 8 miles in length, 4-5 times/week. Before these shoes my shoe of choice was the Adidas Energy Boost 2. When I initially ordered the shoes, I ordered the typical size that I wore in the Boost 2's. However, when the shoes arrived, I tried them on, and they were way too long and especially too loose in the heel. I have a normal width foot, arch, etc. So, I returned the shoes and ordered a new pair, a half size down.
These shoes arrived and at a half size smaller than I normally wear, they fit much closer in style to my Boost 2's. However, they still feel a little loose in the heel and slip when I run up VERY steep hills. Also, my front toes tend to go numb on me when I do longer than 5 mile runs, this does NOT happen with my Boost 2's.
Finally, the cushioning feels like there is more support but it is not as responsive as I had anticipated and on recent runs with the Ultras I have recently experienced foot pain in my heel and in my knee that I have not experienced in over a year.
Who knows? it could just be my foot size and shape, but for the difference in price the Boost 2's give me a much more satisfying ride and less painful experience than the Ultras. I really really wanted to like this shoe, especially after I paid 180.00 for it, but I think I am going to stick with what works for me: Boost 2. Maybe someone else with a different foot shape and not as many running injuries that I have experienced will be successful with this model. But, this just wasn't for me..... and I really really wanted the all white pair. sigh.

column13: Looks like these will be a return only
column14:

I wanted to return and buy a size 6 (since I can't do a simple exchange), but I just can't justify paying twice as much for the same shoe from the same seller. Looks like these will be a return only. I'm disappointed, but I guess this seller- like many others- prices based on size popularity.

I still gave this shoe a 4 since if they had fit I would have given them a 5. The design of the shoe is even better in person and the quality is inline with all the other Iron First heels I own. column6: Nomadic State of Mind JC Sandal
column14:
Too bad, they do feel nice on the feet, until I wore them outside. My toes kept sliding over the end of the shoe, although I ordered a size bigger. Then I remember that some people thought they were "too big", others thought they were "too small", yet there were those who said they were "just right". So I thought about the 'goldilocks phenomenon' & how that could be & realized that shoes today only come in one width. Why isn't anyone talking about that? Maybe they did but I didn't see. My foot is somewhat narrow therefore slips forward & out of the shoe. I do not think this could be corrected with a larger size.

Bottom line: When considering this shoe think about your foot width & how the fit might apply to you. The company would do well to try to solve this dilemma.

column6: VonZipper Elmore Square Sunglasses
column13: perfect for big heads like mine!
column14:
i rarely ever do reviews, but i just had to in this case because of how much i love these sunglasses.

first, i have a BIG HEAD - i'm a tall guy with a large frame and my head is in proportion to my size, it is pretty much torture for me to buy sunglasses because they are always too small. the only sunglasses that fit my head nicely have been Ray Ban's aviator's (in the supersized 62mm variant) and Carrera Speedways (63mm).

when i bought these, i couldn't find any details as to the sizing but heard they were around 58mm or so - i was extremely worried that they would way too small for my head, but they are AWESOME. i can definitely tell you they fit just as nicely as my huge Carrera's and they're definitely the only square type sunglasses that i've come across that have fit me.

beyond the fit, the quality is awesome, the lenses are mirrored but not too dark - so if you're looking to black out the sun, these probably aren't for you, but i find these are super versatile as i can walk in and out on a bright day without feeling the need to take them off or squint my eyes. the arms are wide and thick, which is great for a guy as it looks more masculine, and the build quality is excellent - nice solid feel while still being light.

i cannot recommend these enough, and with Amazon's return policy, you shouldn't hesitate to try either.

column6: Streetcars Men's Saddleback Slip-On Loafer
column14:
I previously owned a pair of these that I bought at Kohl's. They were very soft and comfortable immediately and didn't need a break-in, that's how awesome they were. Kohl's no longer carries this line, so after mine finally broke down after a couple of years (worn alternating with other shoes, so a few times a week), I was happy to see them available on Amazon.

The outside looks pretty much the same, perhaps with some minor differences, but the insole is very different and I found this newer version a bit hard to walk around in. They seem to require a break-in period. I wore them a few hours a day for a couple of days, but they've gotten gradually less comfortable throughout the day to where I couldn't wait to take them off. I've not worn them in a couple of weeks, but will give them another try for short errands to help the break-in along. They look good and feel good when first put on, but they are definitely more firm than the prior version I had.

column14: These boots are AWESOME! Help up WAY better than I initially thought they would, and I get compliments on them all the time! Love!  My original review below: Nice looking boots. They are a bit on the wide side so they're roomy, but the lace up means they're adjustable so that's good. The only thing is the buckle only removes two straps, and the other two are sewn on, so it's a  bit of a hassle to adjust the laces, but theoretically you'd only do it once, then use the zipper from then on. They do look kind of cheap as there's noticeable glue on the front seam, but I'm going to wreck these at Burning Man so I don't care. I'm sure the seller would take an exchange based on this issue but I'm not really complaining. I say, for the price, you can't beat it!

column6: Eagleyes Sport Polarized Colored Pepper Stun Sunglasses Frames Quality with Prescription Polar Polarizing Sunglasses for Women Under Armour Clip on Polar Eyes Sunglasses Men Wayfarer Smith Polarized Sunglasses Suncloud Polar Optics Clip on Wayfarer Clip on Kate Spade Ladies Photochromic Mirrored Sunglasses Serengeti Aviator Polarized Amber Under Armour Polarized Reading Fit Over Berkley Costa Fit
column13: Clear, sharp vision that reduces/eliminates glare
column14:
Wow what a difference these make. These are the true polarized glasses that first came out in stores back East in the '80s. I own two pair of Sunclouds that are polarized, but the difference with Eagleyes is dramatic. The Eagleyes are much clearer. Whatever method of polarization Eagleyes is using, it is superior to others.

Some reviewers felt these glasses were cheaply made, but that is not accurate. They are lighter weight than say the Sunclouds which are made with thicker plastic. The lens is what you're after here and that gives you the clearest, glare free vision and that's what it's all about in the summer sun.

I'm very glad I got this and I thought the price was half what I paid for the Sunclouds. I highly recommend them.

column6: John Fluevog Women's Rose Dunn Boot
column14: Was excited to get these at an even better clearance price from Amazon after they sold out in my size on the Fluevog website. Unfortunately, as soon as I took them out of the box, I had a feeling--correct, it turns out--that I wouldn't be keeping them. They looked suspiciously narrow through the footbed, and while I was able to get them on, with space for thicker socks lengthwise, they were definitely tight across the widest part of my feet, pinching my pinky toes such that it felt my circulation was being restricted. I've never really been a believer in suffering for beauty, so I'm sending them back. However, if you have narrower feet (I'm almost always a 9.5M, but usually need a 10 in many Fluevogs), I'd definitely recommend them. In black, they're basic but not at all boring; they look fabulous on, esp. from the side, and as I can attest from owning other Fluevogs, you'll always get compliments when you wear them.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Stealth 500P Premium Fully Wireless Gaming Headset - DTS Headphone:X 7.1 Surround Sound - PS4
column14: Everything about the original review applies but the right ear speaker snapped inexplicably at the extender. Apparently craftsmanship wasn't really too good either. Don't waste your money.   Original review:  To preface this review, I am an audiophile. When I think about buying earbuds or cans, I typically will put down quite a lot of cash. Sound and sound quality is important and it is easy to tell who has good speakers and who doesn't. Basically, I had a hard time thinking about this review. These cans are way better than the ps4 earbuds that come with the system, but they are not worth 130$. Basically, these are about 20$-40$ headphones but because they have the ps4 logo on them and they work with the ps4, they basically charge whatever they want.  I sort of knew this coming into this specific market but I didn't think it was that bad. My friends said turtle beaches are the best thing ever and if these are what they are charging close to 150$ for, I don't even want to know their 300$ model. At that price point, you can buy close to studio monitor cans, almost. My guess is that you get something still not worth it but slightly better. There is definitely 7.1 though... but don't be too impressed with the .1. From what I can tell, it has a lousy flabby base that is very loud but not precise, no treble worth a damn, and mids that are acceptable, but not very good.  That said, the wireless works beautifully. It comes from an optical to bluetooth usb device that plugs into the front port of the ps4. Also the boom mic is very stable and well made. They are very comfortable as well. It is unfortunately made out of plastic. I would have prefered metal at this price point but I guess they can sell them for 130$ so they do. It seemed basically that they spent a lot of time and effort to make them wearable and work with the ps4 and put in lousy speakers. Still better than the ear buds though. I am not impressed.

column6: HORI Real Arcade Pro 4 Kai for PlayStation 4, PlayStation 3, and PC
column13: Good budget stick, not mod friendly
column14:
So I'm back on Amazon doing another stick review. This time it's for the HORI RAP 4 Kai. This is currently the cheapest current generation stick on the market which makes it worth a look.

Lets start out with the good. You have a great price point. With at least $50 less than the competition means that it's going to get some looks. It has a carrying handle which makes it really easy to transport. It's a bit lighter than the competition and definitely has a smaller frame which means you are going to have no problem putting this into specialized bags for sticks are just common backpacks. The frame is really solid and doesn't feel like it's going to give at all because of the metal frame. The grip on the bottom of the is nice and makes sure you won't scratch anything the stick is on as well as making sure it won't slide. The cord length is also great along with the compartment. Really big and the cord is really easy to store.

Now lets move to the bad. Unlike the other two sticks in the compassion currently this stick is not easily opened. The other thing is once you open up this stick you void the warranty. The buttons aren't really as good as the competitions but they aren't horrible. They are also easily replaced. The lever is about the same. The only thing that is bad about it is that it's harder to change the gate. The Hayabusa lever has the gate screwed in and it's a lot bigger than a Sanwa gate. You can put a Sawna octagon gate in it's place and usually it stays. It just doesn't clip or screw into place. Some people will not be happy with the base of the stick because it's not as wide as the others so there is a smaller place to rest your hands. Also in the inside there is a lot of glue, so it's harder to change out wires or see what wires go where because there is glue over the labels. Last thing is that space isn't at a premium with this stick so you won't be able to add things in as easily.

All in all thisstick is a decent stick. Especially at the price point. I would say if you have the money you should get the T.E.2. If you don't this is a stick that will work and you can always swap out everything to sanwa parts to improve the performance.

column6: Ortz PS4 Vertical Stand with Cooling Fan [Charges 4 Controllers]
column13: Good product that is delicate like a flower
column14:
The good: It does exactly what it is supposed to. All the controllers fit in there fine and the fans work great to keep the console cool.

The bad: It is difficult to describe, but when you put the controllers in their slot, most of the time, it doesn't feel like they are connected. It would have been nice to have a lite on the side to indicate that the controller is connected. You pretty much have to pull up on the controller to see if the connection plug will have any resistance. This problem is exacerbated by the cheap plastic feel of the thing. I often worry I might break the connection plug if the controller isn't aligned just right. So far that hasn't happened, so I hate to call it a bad, but I suspect my kids will not pay attention one day and destroy it.

The annoying: I like to play in the dark. There is an LED on the front of this thing that is wicked bright. It pierces my eyes like Apollo himself placed the sun in my living room. I fixed it with a little black electrical tape so it isn't a big deal.

Overall: Good product and is super handy if you have a lot of controllers that get used often. I would recommend to buy, just be mindful that you'll have to treat it with care.

column6: The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt
column14:
I'm very confused by the ratings for this game. I keep thinking I'm missing something but when try to go back and play it still find myself underwhelmed. I have about 7 hours and cant find myself trying to get to 8.

The graphics in this game are beautiful. Character faces are incredibly detailed and I'm impressed with the small things such as the glint coming from the characters sword.

Leveling up and the talent tree is complex and very well done. No complaints in that area.

The character is very dull and boring... with seemingly little to no emotion. He talks with that gritty batman tone except he is monotone most of the time. I wouldn't mind so much but the game is incredibly story driven so you have to listen to it.

I dont like the controls. I have tried both, the keyboard/mouse and xbox controller. I find myself annoyed with engaging in battle. I'm constantly trying to target the enemy but by the time I get close enough to do so they see you and start running toward you. After backing up a bit the enemy runs back to it's original location like nothing happened. If you draw your bow and shoot it from a distance and you're not within its "agro range" it doesn't do anything. I hate trying to fight within their little agro bubble without coming out of it. Movement is annoying. Sometimes I run in circles trying to get on my horse or try to pickup something. I'm also constantly turning on or off lamps or candles for some reason. Why are they there?

There are quite a few missions that you have to complete in a detective style approach which gets annoying fast. I thought it was only for a couple of the first few missions but it seems that these types of missions are throughout the game. Please, I do not want to use my batman senses and follow footprints or blood trails around.

Herbs are scattered around the map everywhere. I found myself grabbing as many herbs as I could until I realized you only need to learn to make a potion once then you know it forever. Not sure why there are soooo many of these around. Not sure what the point is.

Blacksmithing in this game is incredibly stupid.

The game is open world but each area is broken into little quest zones where quests seemingly repeat themselves.

I could go on and on. The game's just not for me.

column6: Nintendo Amiibo
column13: Functions like all other amiibo, but looks especially nice while doing it.
column14:
The Palutena figure performs all of the same basic functions as any of the amiibo used in Super Smash Bros. for 3DS / Wii U. You can customize and level up the figure as an "FP" or "Figure Player", which is a computer player that learns and gains experience as you fight it. There's not much else to do with the figure in terms of software (Palutena is only compatible with Smash as of this writing), but being able to customize and train your own fighting machine is a fun experience, and certainly adds some extra things to do in Smash if you're playing solo.

As for the quality of the figure herself, Palutena's paint job is phenomenal. Her face looks well proportioned (no wonky eyes here!), the accessories are all coated nicely, and overall I would say that this is the nicest amiibo from the Super Smash Bros. line released yet!

Not to mention the actual process of ordering was so much easier than it has been in the past.

column6: Super Mario 3D Land
column13: Awesome Mario game, 7 y/o son (and dad) love it!
column14:
Bought this for my 7 y/o son. Everything you love about classic Mario games all the way through the Galaxy series. I've played tons of Mario, and the levels are challenging as usual but nothing too difficult. My son has had a lot of time on the game, and really loves it, replays levels multiple times because it's just fun.

If there was any negative, it'd be that it's maybe TOO easy to get extra lives. They're everywhere, and coins are constantly all over everything (and every 100 coins = extra life). Step on a goomba? Get a coin (or two, or three!). Bump a few bushes, coins. Slide down the pole? Extra life if you hit the top, plus coins, plus coins for all the seconds you have remaining in the level. It would actually be MORE difficult to run out of lives than not. My son has in two weeks accumulated 300+ extra lives. It's a bit unnecessary, but it's not like it hurts the gameplay. You just know you're never going to actually run out of lives, so what's the point of having them?

column13: Hours and Hours of FUN!  We literally spend our entire weekends playing this game 24/7
column14: This game has brought hours and hours of enjoyment to our household. We do mostly vocals, bass, ProKeys, and 5-lane Keys. We love the song choices and love the ability to integrate the older versions of the game into this newer version, which increases the number of songs available to us. The DLC is a really good selection, and if you're really looking for an adventure, I highly recommend purchasing from the RBN library (in the online in-game marketplace) for an even larger selection.  As Harmonix has decided to no longer produce DLC for this game, this particular version, the EA version, makes it easy to play custom songs offline (just don't play them online!)  And now that RockBand 4 will soon be available, I firmly believe this version will still be popular as the are many features that will be missing in the new RB4, such as online play.

column6: Xbox One with Kinect (Day One Edition)
column13: Great system, but not without flaws
column14:
I have been an xbox supporter since the original, and I have to say there are a lot of things that I love about it, but a few things that I hate.
Pros: The controller feels great. The kinect is actually quite handy. I love the voice controls, but I wish there were more games that utilized it. Other than that, the game selection is great. Right now, I would say it's about on par with Playstations lineup, but the list of xbox exclusives is growing and the next year I think xbox will gain the edge. They recently announced backwards compatibility from 360 games too, which is HUGE. One of my biggest gripes in the beginning was how they claimed the One was supposed to be the all in one media center to take over you're living room, but still need my 360 because of the many games I already have invested in it. Finally the blu ray player is a great addition and something that was sorely lacking from 360.
Cons: The interface slightly clunky but not too bad. The large tiles feel like it was made for a touch screen, but navigating it with a controller is not quite as easy. The biggest complaint I have is with the social aspect. Parties are not even as easy to form as they were on 360 and they are unreliable. Also it is extremely difficult to send a message to someone who isn't on you're friends list, so if you play Destiny specifically and are a fan of destinylfg, you know the struggle.
Verdict: I have had the Xbox One for almost a year now and I still love it. It's not perfect, but it's been constantly getting better via monthly updates. Microsoft seems like they are listening to feedback and really trying to fine tune everything. Also the lineup of games that is coming on the horizon is going to destroy my wallet.

column6: Zettaguard Wireless PC USB Gaming Receiver for Xbox 360 Compact Disc
column13: Not plug-and-play setup, but does indeed work with some effort.
column14:
I intended to buy Microsoft brand receivers but bought these by mistake. I decided to give them a try. I was able to get these to work in Windows 7 Ultimate 64 bit and 32 bit, OS X 10.1.1, and Linux Mint.

For windows I followed the instructions others have posted here. I had to do this for every USB port I wanted to be able to use the device from, but it did work.

For OS X, I installed the driver located here: https://github.com/d235j/360Controller/releases
I installed v0.14 at the time. Works great, althought I did have to restart my computer and install it a couple times before it seemed to work consistently.

For Linux mint, I installed the xboxdrv driver using ubunt-xboxdrv located here: https://launchpad.net/~rael-gc/+archive/ubuntu/ubuntu-xboxdrv

I wish the windows setup had been easier. It takes work to get these things to actually function, but once you do they seem to work fine. I think the setup difficulties are worth the cost savings, but I'm computer savvy. For a hass... Read more

column6: The Sims 2 Happy Holiday Stuff
column14:
I am a hardcore sims 2 fan, and this was one of the last "expansion packs" i had to get. It did add a lot to the game, the holiday decorations (some halloween, a cornucopia for thanksgiving, party poppers, sparklers, noisemakers, for new years, a menorah, plus many many many christmas decorations!) were fantastic, and coupled with the seasons pack, it really added life to the game.

However.

There is a rather common glitch with this pack, and there is almost no way to fix it. The clothes dont load into the game. No clothes are present at all, and because the game cant "find" the clothes, santa claus and father time are EXTREMELY glitched. They wont mess up your game, but it is so disappointing to find that santas face is completely invisible and hes wearing a default business suit. There is no way to fix it, as the holiday pack melds itself into the base game data and cant be deleted unless you delete the ENTIRE game. Maybe this wont happen to you, and i still recommend the pack, but please back up your game before installing it so that if this does happen to you, you may be able to fix it with a complete uninstall and replace your game with the backed up files. Just a word of warning!

column6: Xbox One Halo: The Master Chief Collection 500GB with Second Controller and Assassin's Creed IV Black Flag Bundle
column14:
A lot of research went into this purchase. I searched every kind of bundle every retail store had to find the most cost effective one there is and this one could not be beat. At least for me. Allow me to explain.

I had no intention of buying this bundle for the games (Digital copy of Halo: Master Chief Collection and a physical copy of Assassin's Creed: Black Flag) mainly because Halo: MCC is not worth touching with a ten foot pole (unless you're into completely buggy and utter failure games) and Assassin's Creed: Black Flag was recently the free game of the month for gold members.¬†

No no no no. That is hardly a steal. In fact, I plan to sell both to make some kind of coin back, if any. (I spoke to Gamestop today and they're willing to take Assassin's Creed: Black Flag for a whopping $1.50. I don't even think driving to my nearest GameStop would be worth that.)

I bought this bundle because of the extra controller it came with. Consider this. If I were to go to most retail stores, like Amazon, and buy a standard 500 GB Xbox One without a Kinect we are looking at roughly $350. With that, I have also discovered that buying a 'wireless controller NEW' separately is fairly costly. Amazon? $47.99. Walmart? $59.00 (Seriously?). Gamestop? See Walmart. So together, buying a standard Kinectless Xbox one and a brand new wireless controller would be roughly $400.¬†

So it is obvious that buying this bundle at $350 is the most cost effective purchase of most Xbox One bundles even out there.¬†

So here are a few side notes about this bundle that aren't already stated in this review or in the description (And if they are oh well haha).
-It comes with a headset. Handle with care! Although the microphone is surprisingly great quality, the flimsy frame can bust very easily if tossed around or accidentally sat on.
-Batteries are indeed included! Controllers require AA batteries and while I recommend buying rechargeable batteries, you can use the batteries it comes with for now.
-Mine came with a 14 day Gold pass. I'd assume yours will too.

That's it for notes! I think this was a great purchase and I would highly recommend this buy for anyone.¬†

column6: Alien: Isolation
column13: Gave two stars at first out of frustration
column14: So maybe I was quick to bash this game. I thought this game would be like Dead Space but I was very mistaken. The sound is great, I like the visual aspects of it, and the environment is creepy but overall its an average game.  I got bored with it quickly. Sneaking around and avoiding conflict can entertain only so much. Not my cup of tea.  It starts slow and then gets a little better. But to sum it up: The Alien cannot be killed! I probably died at least 30 times. At first it was exhilarating to get caught by the Alien and killed in different ways, but then it quickly got frustrating in some parts having to replay it over and over.   Actually I thought the game got better once the Alien was gone for awhile. Gave me time to explore and find collectibles. And once I found the flamethrower the confrontations with the Alien got less frustrating.   With a few tweaks here and there as far as (saving points, better stealth system, a little more action, an Alien that can be hurt) this game can be great. It has a lot of potential.

column6: SteelSeries Siberia P300 Comfortable Gaming Headset for PlayStation 4, PlayStation 3
column14:
The SteelSeries Siberia P300 headphones work well. I am quite happy with the overall quality.

First, the build quality is excellent. I like the way the inner headband stretches a bit so the headphones can fit comfortably on my head. They feel lighter than I would have expected given the size. The ear cups feel comfortable on my ears for the most part. The none issue I have with any over the ear headphones is that when I wear my glasses with the headphones on, the sides of my ears start to hurt.

Second, the sound quality of these headphones is great. Everything sounds crisp and clear. I love how the microphone can easily be adjusted and the switch on the ear that allows muting.

Overall, these headphones are a solid choice for people who play a lot of multi-player games.

column6: Star Wars Episode III Revenge of the Sith - PlayStation 2
column13: One of the better movie tie in games.
column14: Overall the game is a decent game. I remember it far too fondly as a kid and attempted to recapture that nostalgia of days gone past. Technically speaking their is nothing wrong with the game, however there is nothing exceptional about it either. The cut scenes are mostly ripped right from the movie and they compliment the main story quite well. The game has quite a few turret sections and tends to be a lot of wait for enemies to spawn so that you can kill them and leave the room. column6: Nyko Xbox One USB Charge Base
column14:
I liked this product. I needed a wireless charger, since Microsoft is too cheap to include a wireless charger with your already-expensive purchase of the Xbox One. The device charges quickly. I also found that you can use the remote while it's charging. It's not the most comfortable way to do so, but it still works if you don't want to step away from the action.

The only thing that prevented me from giving it five stars was the sometimes difficulty with getting the remote to rest comfortably to charge. I found that I had to adjust it several ways to make sure it was charging. There were even times when it would start charging, but I would find an hour in that the controller had moved a niggling amount, causing it to not charge the whole time.

Other than that, I would recommend you pick this up. As long as you don't mind fiddling around with it occasionally, you won't go wrong.

Real players, real areas, real musicians. That's how a skate game is made to be. Konami did not disappoint with this particular game. One might call it a masterpiece while some might say it's a piece of somethin else. But in all, the game is a variant from the others out there. It helps to get out of your THPS comfort zone and get your mind working like a real skateboarder (plus, you have to use gravity as a variable in this game).

column6: Call of Duty: Ghosts
column14: First off, it's a call of duty game. I never had high expectations for this game's storyline or its innovations. Maybe that is why I thought it was an amazing game. I have played every Call of Duty game since The Big Red One, and this has my second favorite story (behind Black Ops 1) and favorite game mechanics. Yeah it's bombastic and unrealistic. It's also a video game. I'll admit they should have omitted the second space mission (the first one was so cool and new, but the second felt unnecessary), but I have no complaints otherwise. I have yet to play online, but the bots actually seem smarter in this game. Less like omniscient losers (I'm looking at you Black Ops 2) and more like actual opponents. I have to work for my points but I don't feel cheated out of them. And the new stabbing mechanic is wonderful. The aliens modes are a bit disappointing, but I didn't pay 60 dollars for this game. I paid about 10. And at 10 dollars this game is well worth your time.

column6: Watch Dogs
column13: You are insane if you don't buy this for $10.
column14:
rating this 4 stars as the price is about $10. As long as you get it for this price, you are golden.

The large world they created is nice, but not close in size to gta5. It's similar though and I'm not sure all that extra 'unvisited space' matters for most people. They do have a very nice and tight story to the game. I enjoyed the combat more over the combat in gtaV. The story is also better in my opinion. It's well worth $10 and if you haven't picked it up, do so. I wouldn't give the same recommendation at $60, $50 or even $40, but this is a good game at a now bargain price.

I played on 'easy', and loved it... as I generally 'suck' at these type of game, but wanted to enjoy the story. You veteran shooters will obviously choose a higher difficulty level. It's a great game, though it does have it's flaws.. however, for $10, I think you can overlook them.

column6: 007 Legends
column14:
This turned out to be an OK FPS, but it was also one of the most disappointing Bond games of all time. Both 007 Legends and Goldeneye: Reloaded started off with awesome concepts that they ultimate fumbled. The latter ended up not being a remake of the classic game, but a completely new game that serves as a remake of the film with Daniel Craig in the lead. Which was pretty cool, but not what most of us wanted, a modernized version of the best Bond game ever. 007 Legends seemed like was going to be a celebration of 50 Years of Bond in video game form. Playing through the classic films as Sean Connery, Roger Moore, etc. There would be Goldfinger, On Her Majesty's Secret Service, Moonraker, License To Kill, Die Another Day and Skyfall. But it turned out to just be a tie-in with Skyfall, in which Bond (while unconscious after being shot by Moneypenny in the opening moments of Skyfall) dreams about the events of those films. But once again the events have been reimagined as taking place in the Daniel Craig era, who you play as through all these missions. It reuses the game engine, and really the premise, of Goldeneye: Reloaded, so it's basically just more of the same.

As far as Gameplay goes, I found both of these games to be a step back. It's essentially a Call Of Duty knock-off, which doesn't really fit the Bond style. Unless they were doing a remake of Goldeneye N64, we've gotten past straight-forward shoot-em-ups. Games like Quantum Of Solace and Blood Stone had incorporated the espionage elements of the films, and gave players the opportunity to stealthily sneak through and take down opponents in hand to hand combat or silenced weapons. Of course if you wanted to you could just plow through with guns blazing, but the choice was yours. That's not the case with these two most recent games though, they're just arcade style shooters that don't really capture the spirit of the franchise.

Still, as a hardcore Bond fan I did enjoy playing it. Just the curiosity of seeing how they treated the events of those films as well as seeing some familiar faces in various Bond girls, villains and their henchmen. As they still use the original likenesses of the supporting cast in this game, unlike Goldeneye: Reloaded where they used different likenesses for all the characters. If you're not really that into the movies I can't recommend this game though. There are better FPS games, and better Bond games.

column6: Destiny
column14: This game was relatively enjoyable for a few weeks. It mostly revolves around flying to several different planets and running through piles of mobs and killing them to get to a boss encounter. There is a decent amount of variety in the enemy types, but it will eventually get old. The backstory is pretty lacking, and I couldn't shake the feeling that I was never really getting to understand what exactly my character was doing or why. Still, I think the gameplay and coop experience was fun enough to be worth the purchase.

I have played many past Elder Scrolls games, Morrowind, Oblivion, Skyrim, with various bonus packs. This game is somehow not the same, and yet not different, than the prior games. It has aspects of all the prior games (sadly without dragons) but adds tons of new features and a new world to explore. I think they are still in the process of updating and improving the gameplay. Keep in mind my PC meets or exceeds the "recommended" system and fast internet, so I don't have glitches like others have reported. Anyway, here are a few things to share:

PROS
* I got this game for a steal. List price is $60, I got for $32 (incl tax). Includes unlimited gameplay (yes truly unlimited, no need to buy a monthly subscription), and a couple bonuses like a beginner companion and the ability to play any race with any affiliation. You can choose to pay real money to get "crowns," which is a currency used to buy upgrades and special things (e.g., mounts) from the crown store. But there is certainly no need to! Honestly, $32 (or even $60) for so many hours of entertainment is a complete steal.
* Like all other ES games, it is a huge world that you are free to explore at your own pace. Many quests to choose from, and you can pick and choose which to work on. Or you can explore. Or interact. Or PVP. Or hunt monsters. Or collect books. Or work on fulfilling achievements. The possibilities are "unlimited".
* Character creation and development allows you to personalize your character with great detail and develop them in a manner that conforms to your play style. For example, my typical character is always stealthy and uses a bow, which means my progress and exploration is slower but equally fulfilling. I was able to create the perfect character, although it took awhile to get my first bow.
* Rewarding gameplay - I have played a few hours each day for a week and am already Level 8. However, it is still challenging and I've died more than a few times.
* You can create up to 8 different characters to play, so the choices are truly unlimited!
* Ever been stuck in a situation where you get ambushed by too many creatures you can't handle alone? There are groups and guilds to adventure together! Each group can help since each person might have a different style of game play. However, I do always see ads for groups seeking healers, so there seems to be an uneven balance of players. Unfortunately, my style of gameplay is less valued in the group setting, so I will be playing more alone.
* Decent tutorial. Plus there is a special area/quest line based on your affiliation (mine is Bleakrock), which is a good area for lower players to get more experience.
* Some things are well organized. Like your inventory divides into subsections. Your journal divides into subsections by Main, Crafting, Guilds, etc. There are buttons and tabs everywhere if you can find them!

CONS
* Took a long time to install. 4 disks plus patches. I finally gave up and went to bed so couldn't play my first day.
* Running into some glitches with patch updates. I keep getting a popup box that a patch is causing problems, and sometimes it wants me to "Repair" which takes a few minutes. Frustrating that there is not a better method for patching that avoids such errors.
* Carrying capacity - Like all past ES games, this is a challenge from the beginning. You start with 60 inventory spaces and have to buy expansions (which give you 10 more slots but cost exponentially more). You can also store things in your bank, which again starts at 60 slots and you have to buy expansions. There are so many different things you can pick up int he game that this is quite disappointing. For example, you need 10 iron ore to make iron ingot, and to actually craft you also need a style piece (e.g., bone) and optional trait. Then you can upgrade, but that is more items to collect and carry. There are like 6 different crafts in the game, each requiring a dozen or more items to collect. Not to mention the hundreds or thousands of other items!
* Map system could use improvement. The maps of Skyrim and even Oblivion were better than the map in ESO. Here, you have only major sites marked on your map, not smaller ones. The map is not very flexible in terms of zooming in/out, and when you're inside a city like Davon's Watch, you may or may not be able to see the map markers for quests outside the city.
* Travel could use improvement. Travel has always been an issue with ES games. In ESO, you have Wayshrines to travel between. You have to first find the wayshrines. Does it cost gold to travel between wayshrines? I dunno, I read a guide that said it costs, but then there are no popups in the game to tell you how much. Also the wayshrines are far apart and the only other way is your feet or a mount (which is expensive and you don't get until later in the game). You can also quicktravel to wayshrines from anywhere, but this costs. If you are in a group, you can travel to your group members, but the way to do this is cumbersome.
* Chat - I imagine like many other MMORPG games, there are some seriously messed up people using chat, and there is often very crude language and things posted for all to see. These people should be ashamed of themselves, and it sucks I have to read all that on my screen. I would like the ability to "flag" players who harass others or post inappropriate things, and have that person be banned from chat for a time or fined or something. But yeah, it's the chat feature and not the game itself that would make me reluctant to let kids or teens play this game.
* Stealing is much harder than past ES games. As a shadow character, I always relied on stealing. But in ESO, I have only found one fence location so far (by level 8), and it sucks to have to travel there each time (Plus you have to travel to the nearby wayshrine, then run/walk your way through the city until you get to the fence, it is slow). I often get caught stealing, because even when you are showing as "hidden," you can get caught by someone spotting you while you have the container window open, or you get caught when trying to pickpocket someone rather than when you try to "collect" something from their pocket. Stealing is no fun anymore, even though you basically need to rely on it for gold.
* There is no thieves guild! This was my favorite guild in past games.
* There is so much that it is often overwhelming and confusing at times. For example, you press C for Character and K for Skills, and all sorts of other letters for different things. Thankfully these are laid out in the pamphlet that came with the game. But there are many other instructions not provided, like how to chat, how to interact, guilds, and most importantly the skill trees. I really liked the galaxy skill trees from Skyrim so this is a bit disappointing and confusing. There is no explanation as to "active" and "passive" skills, when/how you can get what, or really how to use them. You just have to test it out for yourself (and might end up killing an NPC or pet in the process of testing). You don't get skill points back, so researching them ahead of time is a must. Also, there are no instructions for interacting with the MMO aspects of the game. This being my first MMO (and only because I love the ES line of games), I have no clue about chatting and guilds and groups. Learning by doing because not many online sources discuss this in detail. The game tries to help you with pop instructions here and there, but it is insufficient. Would be better to have a "help" guide stored somewhere in the game to reference how to do something, the game is so complex.

What a Rush! This is why I can never understand the mindset of a Sonic "fan"; not a FAN, but a "fan". You know the kind; the person would crap on anything with Sonic's face on it if it's not exactly like the Sega Genesis trilogy from the 90s. Meanwhile, as the Sonic fan I am, I actually find more gems than lumps of coal in the franchise. Perhaps many of those "fans" lack a handheld system because Sonic the Hedgehog is actually most consistent with its quality on the go; when the Genesis games hogged the spotlight, the Game Gear games provided its own flavor of Sonic action. As the mediocre-ish Sonic Adventure 2 came around and was followed up by Sonic Heroes, the Game Boy Advance delivered its own trilogy of awesome Sonic games using the tried-and-true Sega Genesis formula, with an added burst of speed. When Shadow The Hedgehog was busy being awful, Sonic Rush paved its way to acclaim. And now we have Sonic Rush Adventure, a game that came out after Sonic seemingly betrayed console owners via Sonic 06. Is it as terrible as th-OF COURSE NOT!

Being that Sonic Rush Adventure is a sequel to the first Sonic Rush released two years prior, the game continues to provide some of the best high-speed platforming action since the Game Boy Advance era. As Sonic the Hedgehog or Blaze the Cat, you dash your way through seven Zones, and at the end of each Zone comes a boss battle. There are also additional missions and Special Stages which are needed to get the best ending. Sounds pretty much like the oldschool Sonic formula we know and love! The structure is more elaborate this time around thanks to the whole treasure-hunting theme we have going here, but it's still familiar. Since the Zones are all their own separate islands, the world is spread out over a large ocean containing said islands, as well as various hidden locations. Traveling to these islands means you have to utilize one of what would become an arsenal of four crafts to drive through the water. Initially, you can only use a jetski, but as the game progresses you're able to use a sailboat, submarine, and hovercraft. Each of these vehicles actually provide their own unique gameplay styles, and they work rather well!

The jetski has Sonic in a 3D perspective, but you move him by dragging the stylus left and/or right, dodging things in sight and hitting ramps to pull off sweet tricks, and you can Boost, allowing you to pummel destructible obstacles and gain speed. The hovercraft plays similarly, except you can't boost or find ramps; instead you can shoot and charge up your projectile, as well as do a spin attack. Because the sailboat has weapons aboard, its gameplay is actually more of a shooting-gallery type. And lastly, the submarine has you tap the enemies at proper timings, similarly to the likes of Elite Beat Agents. They're all actually pretty fun and add diversity to the experience as a whole. That isn't to say you should overlook the gameplay that goes on while on an island, though, because that's obviously where Sonic gets to do what he does best. Sonic has a variety of moves he can pull off, like the classic Spin Dash, grinding on foot, Boosting for speed at will, and tricks he can do in mid-air to increase his ability to Boost. The resulting 2D Sonic gameplay is fast and seamless, making each level feel like a rollercoaster ride filled with gorgeous environments and super-upbeat music!

With every Zone there's a boss at the end waiting, and Sonic Rush Adventure tends to end each of the Zones with a bang; while the bosses themselves may not look like the most creative-looking bad guys in the Sonic series a whole, the fights they pull beg to differ! I honestly think these may be some of the most imaginative boss fights I've played in a Sonic game, and while they are rather on the easy side like in the old days, I found myself loving the process of defeating them. I mean seriously! One of the boss fights has Sonic running in 3D onthe bottom screen, and he must bounce up to the top screen via a non-exploding projectile where the boss awaits with two platforms! Not to mention the boss music helps add to these scenes.

Alright, I think I'm done gushing over this game. There is just a lot in here that I can't help but applaud! Sonic's style of play is present and very well accounted for, and the graphics and sound are equally fascinating. This also goes for the new gameplay styles that get introduced upon using the water vehicles. The production values as a whole decorate this game in the best way they could, even if there are still loads of dialogue scenes done through text. Even then, the story is finely told, and the new supporting character Marine is actually not as bothersome as other new characters the series has introduced before. This is also the first Sonic game to feature online versus play, but sadly, with Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection being extinct, you won't be able to play it against strangers around the world anymore (Although I assume it plays something like Sonic Generations in which the players race each other to the finish within the game's levels). Fortunately, the rest of the game is beyond remarkable, and therefore you should totally get it! column6: Nintendo Wii U 32GB Console Splatoon Special Edition Bundle - Black
column13: This is a Best Buy Exclusive
column14:
A lot of people are mentioning that this is cheaper at Best Buy but don't really explain WHY it's cheaper at Best Buy. This Bundle is a Best Buy exclusive. So You can pick it up at a Best Buy Store for $274. That is the exact Deluxe version shown here with the Splatoon download. Honestly it's the best deal and I would suggest (if you can) going to a Best Buy store to pick it up. Even with Taxes it's cheaper than the sellers here on Amazon.

With that said. If your Best Buy's are out of Stock or You're Lazy. The prices here are still fairly reasonable considering. Plus, it really is a great deal for what you get. A lot of people don't mention what this bundle actually includes.

In this Bundle:
-32 GB Wii U
-Splatoon Download ( There is a code you have to scratch off a card and redeem in the Nintendo E Shop )
-Nintendo Land ( it comes Pre-Installed )
-Wii Sports ( I mean not the biggest perk in the world but it's there )

All in all a pretty sweet deal considering. Either way it's worth the money especially if you are on the fence like I was. Pick it up! Splatoon is a super fun and awesome game for all ages alike and the Wii U is nice to have. It's small, light, and it's nice to sit in bed and watch netflix or casually browse Miiverse :P

column6: Xbox Stereo Headsets
column14: The xbox One Stereo headset works perfectly fine. At first i was worried about the mic length or if my friends could hear me, but that wasn't a problem, but I needed to talk loud or askew the headset from the mic side. Though, the mic can turn left and right for a better radius.  The only problem is it feels a bit flimsy and is a bit small. It fits me fine, but i can only imagine for people with small heads. It comes with the headset, very small USB cord (for your controller so you can update its software) and a separate controller adapter which can range from $20 to $30. So the headset in reality is $30. Great product for somewhat light gamers.   UPDATE: It broke :(  The plastic broke off, but it still works. I would not recommend the mic if you have a lot of money to spend, but it lasted a very long time and I still have the small USB cord and the headset adapter which I can use on any other headset or just plain earphones (earphones will not pick up your voice although). All in all, I would buy again, but considering I already have the adapter and USB cable, there should be a price drop.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Stealth 420X Fully Wireless Gaming Headset (Certified Refurbished) - Xbox One
column13: Great wireless headphones for the price
column14: finally a pair of Xbox One wireless headphones that aren't a complete hassle. I previously had the Turtle Beach 500x Stealth headphones and while they sounded great, the wireless connection was terrible. These are a different story. The sound is above average because they're not surround, but stereo sound, which is great if you're not looking for Astro quality sound. But if you're looking for comfort and easy wireless setup (literally plug the receiver in and turn them on, that's it), these are the way to go. I wouldn't recommend them for professional competitive level play (that's the Turtle Beach Elite 800x), but more for playing in silence without bothering anyone. The mic is removable and they can be used as regular headphones for music.

column6: Sudroid carryer bag iHard Case Bag Pouch Cover For PSp 3000/2000/1000 (Silver)
column13: Good quality for an unlicensed product!
column14:
Good quality for an unlicensed product! It isn't much of a "hard" case as described; instead, the clamshell feels a bit spongy, perhaps styrofoam-like. It will probably shrug off several accidental drops without much issue, though you might find your battery cover is loose after a drop. I've never owned or used any official PSP merchandise, though, so I have nothing to compare this to.

No issues with the zipper or clip. The PSP-2001 fits snugly inside, although it can really only be slid in and out one way due to the PSP's button configuration. I only wish there were some room to fit some extra UMDs -- but hey, that's not what this was designed for anyway. There is a velcro attachment inside that allows you to pack two additional Memory Stick Duos in the clamshell opposite the system.

My favorite part is the Engrish on the product's packaging. It made me and my girlfriend chuckle.

Overall, I recommend this product to anyone who's still looking to protect their PSP-2000 or PSP-3000. I'll update if any problems arise!

column6: GAMETECH micro-B to 3DS Power Adapter Charger Cable Converter
column14:
The GAMETECH Micro-USB to 3DS power adapter is a great accessory for those of you who are looking to either cut down on the number of wires you need, or want a larger selection of cord lengths to chose from. This accessory is compatible with 3DS, 3DS XL/LL, New 3DS, New 3DS XL/LL, DSi, and DSi XL/LL.

If you use a USB battery pack (Anker, RAVPower, etc) and normally pair it with micro-USB, you'll benefit greatly from this accessory. Instead of having a micro-USB and a 3DS power cable, you just need the micro-USB cord and this small adapter to charge your devices. The adapter is small, less than an inch in length, so I suggest getting a wrist strap for your 3DS and looping the adapter through it (see images) to keep it from getting lost. Doing so is also convenient because it will always be on your 3DS when you need it.

If you find that your 3DS power cord length is too short or too long, this adapter will help you. Since the selection of 3DS power cords for purchase is minimal just about everywhere, you could get this adapter to expand your selection to micro-USB cords as well. For instance, if you want a 15 foot 3DS charging cable, you'd be hard pressed to find one. However, with this accessory, you could instead find a 15 foot micro-USB cable (which is much easier to find).

Will your 3DS charge slower with this accessory? The simple answer is no. This is just an adapter, it doesn't really change anything. The power source and the micro-USB cable that you choose will be the limiting factors. If you plug this accessory into a wall charger that you use for your phone, you should be fine. Most phone chargers are rated between 1A and 2.4A (5V), which is still greater than the 3DS's 900mA (5V) rating anyways. If you plug this accessory into your computer, you will be getting 500mA out of the rated 900mA (5V) charge rate of the 3DS which will take roughly twice as long to charge to full capacity unless you have a USB 3.0 port which is rated at 900mA (5V) which will charge at full speed.

The adapter is currently a little pricey ($8) since you could just buy an off-brand 3DS charger cable for less. However, I think that this cable is very convenient and is more than worth it for someone who wants to cut down on cords, or uses an external battery pack.rge at full speed. column6: GAEMS Vanguard Personal Gaming Environment
column14:
i ordered this product via Amazon warehouse and it was stated to have slight damage to the outside of the case. I couldn't be happier with the g190. All that was missing was the logo.
The screen is a great size and has no glare even in direct sunlight. I am even able to play with a friend and share the screen with no problems at all. The speakers leave a little to be desired but are more than adequate for their size. It also has two headphone jacks even you'd prefer. I was able to fit an Xbox one, all cables and power supplies (including the screens power supply), and one controller in the box without any problems. I don't think you can fit two controllers in it with the Xbox one, but maybe could with a ps4 being that there's no power brick. There is room to put a couple of game boxes on top of the console and shut the lid without them touching the screen but I don't feel comfortable with them sliding around in there. But you could if you were so inclined.
I travel with this to and from work on a river boat and so far it's been great. I set it up and take it down daily with no problems. Perfect little gaming set up.

column6: The Elder Scrolls Online
column13: ... gotten enough of the game in to write a good review. I have a V10 healer and have ...
column14: So I've been playing since launch and I think I've finally gotten enough of the game in to write a good review.  I have a V10 healer and have done almost everything other than end game trials and some of the Craglorn quests.  After the worst day one of any game I've played its fully redeemed itself!  Its by far the most versatile MMO I've ever played.  You can literally play any character or class any way you like, I just played with a rouge healer last night lol.  The amount of content is mind blowing, they even do a pretty good job of mixing up the quests.  The graphics are next gen worthy, the professions have a solid purpose, there are around 30 different dungeons all with normal and hard difficulties.  I could list things I like about it all day!  Some things I think would turn a person off about it is a much smaller list but to be fair ill hit a couple of those too.  IT TAKES OVER YOUR LIFE!!!!  I find myself working my life around research timers and stable upgrades, its kinda embarrassing, my girlfriend even knows the schedule!  If you don't have friends who play it will not be as fun.  Of course you can still play and meet friends but probably not gonna be as fun.  There isn't a centralized auction house.  there is a way to sell things to other players but its done through "guild traders" and you can only sell if youre a part of the guild holding the trader.  This is actually kinda annoying because it makes it hard to develop a secondary market for items.  All-in-all I think its a great game to play with friends and I highly recommend it!
